1
00:00:01,957 --> 00:00:04,032
<i>(Birds Squawking)</i>

2
00:00:13,760 --> 00:00:18,173
(Loud Squawking, Cawing)

3
00:00:23,519 --> 00:00:26,189
(Wings Flapping)

4
00:00:26,689 --> 00:00:29,975
(Chirping, Twittering)

5
00:01:33,255 --> 00:01:36,623
(Squawking Intensifies)

6
00:01:40,928 --> 00:01:42,838
(Cable Car Bell Dinging)

7
00:01:43,014 --> 00:01:45,302
<i>(Squawking Continues)</i>

8
00:01:57,528 --> 00:01:59,604
<i>(Car Horn Honking)</i>

9
00:02:00,448 --> 00:02:02,524
(Boy Wolf Whistles)

10
00:02:04,410 --> 00:02:06,782
(Squawking, Chirping)

11
00:02:16,755 --> 00:02:18,831
(Birds Chirping)

12
00:02:23,095 --> 00:02:26,012
- Hello, Mrs MacGruder.
- Hello, Miss Daniels.

13
00:02:26,181 --> 00:02:29,265
Have you ever seen so many gulls?
What do you suppose it is?

14
00:02:29,434 --> 00:02:33,479
There must be a storm at sea.
That can drive them inland, you know.

15
00:02:33,647 --> 00:02:36,766
I was hoping you'd be a little late.
He hasn't arrived yet.

16
00:02:36,941 --> 00:02:39,017
- But you said 3.00.
- I know.

17
00:02:39,194 --> 00:02:43,939
I know. I've been calling all morning.
You have no idea.

18
00:02:44,115 --> 00:02:47,032
They are so difficult to get.
Really, they are.

19
00:02:47,201 --> 00:02:50,156
We have to get them from India
when they're baby chicks, and then...

20
00:02:50,330 --> 00:02:54,826
- This one won't be a chick, will he?
- Oh, no, certainly not.

21
00:02:55,001 --> 00:02:58,002
- This will be a full-grown mynah bird.
- And he'll talk?

22
00:02:58,588 --> 00:03:00,248
Well, yes, of course he'll...

23
00:03:00,423 --> 00:03:03,708
Well, no, you'll have to teach him to talk.

24
00:03:03,884 --> 00:03:07,929
I guess maybe I'd better phone.
They said 3.00.

25
00:03:08,097 --> 00:03:10,469
Maybe it's the traffic. I'll call.

26
00:03:10,641 --> 00:03:14,935
<i>- Would you mind waiting?
- Well, maybe you'd better deliver him.</i>

27
00:03:15,104 --> 00:03:19,054
- Let me give you my address.
- Oh, well, alright,

28
00:03:19,233 --> 00:03:21,724
but I'm sure they're on the way.

29
00:03:22,194 --> 00:03:24,566
Would you mind if I called?

30
00:03:24,738 --> 00:03:26,814
No. Alright.

31
00:03:44,091 --> 00:03:46,760
<i>- I wonder if you could help me.
- What?</i>

32
00:03:48,095 --> 00:03:51,012
I said, I wonder if you could help me.

33
00:03:53,433 --> 00:03:56,552
Yes. What is it you're looking for, sir?

34
00:03:56,728 --> 00:03:58,804
- Lovebirds.
- Lovebirds, sir?

35
00:03:58,980 --> 00:04:01,268
Yes.
I understand there are different varieties.

36
00:04:01,440 --> 00:04:03,516
- Is that true?
- Well, yes, there are.

37
00:04:03,693 --> 00:04:08,272
These are for my sister for her birthday
and, as she's only going to be 11,

38
00:04:08,448 --> 00:04:12,196
I wouldn't want a pair of birds
that were... too demonstrative.

39
00:04:12,702 --> 00:04:14,611
- I understand completely.
- At the same time,

40
00:04:14,787 --> 00:04:18,488
- I wouldn't want them to be too aloof.
- Of course not.

41
00:04:18,666 --> 00:04:21,667
Do you happen to have
a pair of birds that are... just friendly?

42
00:04:21,836 --> 00:04:25,667
Oh, I think so. Now, then, let me see.

43
00:04:27,382 --> 00:04:30,052
(Chirping Continues)

44
00:04:30,218 --> 00:04:32,793
Aren't those lovebirds?

45
00:04:33,890 --> 00:04:36,843
No. Those are, uh... red birds.

46
00:04:37,017 --> 00:04:39,140
<i>I thought they were strawberry finches.</i>

47
00:04:39,311 --> 00:04:41,719
Yes. We call them that, too.

48
00:04:43,690 --> 00:04:45,766
Here we are. Lovebirds.

49
00:04:47,486 --> 00:04:49,443
Those are canaries.

50
00:04:49,613 --> 00:04:52,816
- Doesn't this make you feel awful?
- Doesn't what make me feel...?

51
00:04:52,991 --> 00:04:56,739
Having all these poor, innocent
creatures caged up like this?

52
00:04:56,911 --> 00:04:59,617
We can't just let them
fly around the shop.

53
00:04:59,790 --> 00:05:01,663
I suppose not.

54
00:05:01,833 --> 00:05:05,451
Is there an ornithological reason
for keeping them in separate cages?

55
00:05:05,629 --> 00:05:09,247
- Certainly. It's to protect the species.
- Yes, that's important,

56
00:05:09,424 --> 00:05:13,042
- especially during the moulting season.
- That's a particularly dangerous time.

57
00:05:13,219 --> 00:05:16,173
- Are they moulting now?
- Some of them are.

58
00:05:16,973 --> 00:05:19,049
How can you tell?

59
00:05:19,517 --> 00:05:23,562
Well, they...
get a sort of hangdog expression.

60
00:05:26,858 --> 00:05:29,064
Yes, I see.
Well, what about the lovebirds?

61
00:05:29,235 --> 00:05:31,062
Are you sure you wouldn't like
to see a canary instead?

62
00:05:31,237 --> 00:05:34,321
We have some very nice
canaries this week.

63
00:05:34,490 --> 00:05:36,566
Alright.

64
00:05:37,576 --> 00:05:39,984
Alright. May I see it, please?

65
00:05:53,509 --> 00:05:55,585
Oh! Oh!

66
00:05:56,512 --> 00:05:59,382
(Mrs MacGruder) What is it? Oh! Oh!

67
00:05:59,556 --> 00:06:01,845
<i>(Mrs MacGruder) Oh! Oh! Oh!</i>

68
00:06:03,310 --> 00:06:05,386
<i>(Miss Daniels) Oh! Oh!</i>

69
00:06:12,819 --> 00:06:14,313
<i>There we are.</i>

70
00:06:14,487 --> 00:06:16,397
- Oh, there.
- Wonderful.

71
00:06:19,618 --> 00:06:23,450
Back in your gilded cage,
Melanie Daniels.

72
00:06:23,622 --> 00:06:27,833
- What did you say?
- I was merely drawing a parallel.

73
00:06:28,001 --> 00:06:31,915
<i>- How did you know my name?
- A little birdie told me.</i>

74
00:06:32,088 --> 00:06:34,579
Good day, Miss Daniels. Madam.

75
00:06:34,757 --> 00:06:38,589
Hey, wait a minute. I don't know you.

76
00:06:38,761 --> 00:06:41,253
- Ah, but I know you.
- How?

77
00:06:41,431 --> 00:06:45,096
- We met in court.
- We never met in court or anyplace else.

78
00:06:45,268 --> 00:06:48,222
- I'll rephrase it. I saw you in court.
- When?

79
00:06:48,396 --> 00:06:50,472
<i>Don't you remember your practical joke</i>

80
00:06:50,648 --> 00:06:52,439
that resulted in the smashing
of a plate-glass window?

81
00:06:52,608 --> 00:06:56,440
<i>- I didn't break that window.
- Yes, but your little prank did.</i>

82
00:06:56,612 --> 00:06:58,688
The judge should have put you
behind bars.

83
00:06:58,864 --> 00:07:02,482
<i>- What are you, a policeman?
- I merely believe in the law.</i>

84
00:07:02,659 --> 00:07:04,568
And I'm not too keen on practical jokers.

85
00:07:04,745 --> 00:07:08,245
- What do you call your lovebird story?
- I really wanted the lovebirds.

86
00:07:09,041 --> 00:07:10,998
You knew I didn't work here.
You deliberately -

87
00:07:11,168 --> 00:07:13,244
<i>Right, I recognised you when I came in.</i>

88
00:07:13,420 --> 00:07:16,706
I thought you might like to know what
it's like to be on the other end of a gag.

89
00:07:16,882 --> 00:07:19,633
<i>- What do you think of that?
- I think you're a louse.</i>

90
00:07:19,801 --> 00:07:22,921
I am. Good day, Miss Daniels. Madam.

91
00:07:25,181 --> 00:07:29,226
- I'm glad you didn't get your lovebirds.
- I'll find something else.

92
00:07:29,394 --> 00:07:31,303
See you in court.

93
00:07:34,816 --> 00:07:37,817
- Who was that man?
- I have no idea.

94
00:07:49,163 --> 00:07:51,239
<i>(Cable Car Bell Dinging)</i>

95
00:08:03,970 --> 00:08:06,924
They said the mynah bird
would be here later this afternoon

96
00:08:07,098 --> 00:08:10,217
- if you'd care to come back.
- No, you'd better send him.

97
00:08:10,392 --> 00:08:13,512
<i>- May I use this phone?
- Why, certainly.</i>

98
00:08:22,904 --> 00:08:27,448
Daily News? It's Melanie Daniels.
Could you get me the City Desk?

99
00:08:27,618 --> 00:08:29,776
<i>Just a minute, Mrs MacGruder.</i>

100
00:08:29,954 --> 00:08:32,029
Hello, Charlie. Melanie.

101
00:08:32,206 --> 00:08:34,578
I want you to do a favour for me.

102
00:08:34,750 --> 00:08:36,826
No, this is a small one.

103
00:08:38,420 --> 00:08:43,128
Pressure you? Why, Charlie, darling,
would I try to pressure you?

104
00:08:43,299 --> 00:08:46,751
Would you call the Department
of Motor Vehicles for me?

105
00:08:46,928 --> 00:08:51,507
Find out who owns this licence plate:
WJH 003.

106
00:08:51,683 --> 00:08:54,174
Yes, a California plate.

107
00:08:54,352 --> 00:08:58,564
No. I'll stop off in a little while.
Is Daddy in his office?

108
00:08:59,023 --> 00:09:03,566
No, I don't want to break in on
a meeting. Tell him I'll see him later.

109
00:09:03,736 --> 00:09:05,812
Thank you, Charlie.

110
00:09:10,117 --> 00:09:13,700
- Do you have any lovebirds?
- Well, no, not in the shop,

111
00:09:13,871 --> 00:09:17,157
<i>- but I can order them for you.
- How soon?</i>

112
00:09:17,333 --> 00:09:20,619
<i>- Well, when would you want them?
- Immediately.</i>

113
00:09:20,795 --> 00:09:24,839
<i>I could probably have them by tomorrow
morning. Would that be alright?</i>

114
00:09:25,007 --> 00:09:27,296
That would be just fine.

115
00:09:35,392 --> 00:09:37,468
(Chirping)

116
00:09:40,647 --> 00:09:43,732
<i>(Door Slides Closed, Lift Hums)</i>

117
00:09:53,368 --> 00:09:56,404
<i>(Door Slides Open)</i>

118
00:10:17,850 --> 00:10:21,017
- Miss, is that for Mitch Brenner?
- Yes.

119
00:10:21,187 --> 00:10:23,393
<i>- He's not home.
- That's alright.</i>

120
00:10:23,564 --> 00:10:26,518
He won't be back until Monday.
I mean, if those birds are for him.

121
00:10:26,692 --> 00:10:28,151
<i>- Monday?
- Yes.</i>

122
00:10:28,319 --> 00:10:30,726
<i>I don't think you should
leave them in the hall, do you?</i>

123
00:10:30,904 --> 00:10:32,862
Well, where did he go?

124
00:10:33,032 --> 00:10:35,867
Bodega Bay.
He goes there every weekend.

125
00:10:36,035 --> 00:10:38,407
- Bodega Bay. Where's that?
- Up the coast.

126
00:10:38,579 --> 00:10:42,280
- About 60 miles north of here.
- Sixty miles... Oh!

127
00:10:42,458 --> 00:10:46,621
<i>It's 1� hours by freeway, or two hours
if you take the coast highway.</i>

128
00:10:47,504 --> 00:10:52,711
I'd look after them myself, but
I'm going away too. I'm awfully sorry.

129
00:10:57,931 --> 00:11:00,008
(Engine Revving)

130
00:11:01,518 --> 00:11:04,140
(Tyres Screeching)

131
00:12:33,274 --> 00:12:35,350
(Bell Rings)

132
00:12:42,617 --> 00:12:44,444
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

133
00:12:44,619 --> 00:12:47,288
- I wonder if you could help me.
- I'll try my best.

134
00:12:47,455 --> 00:12:50,290
<i>- I'm looking for a Mitchell Brenner.
- Yeah.</i>

135
00:12:50,458 --> 00:12:51,489
<i>- Do you know him?
- Yeah.</i>

136
00:12:51,668 --> 00:12:53,993
<i>- Where does he live?
- Right here, Bodega Bay.</i>

137
00:12:54,170 --> 00:12:57,835
- Yes, I know, but where?
- Right across the bay there.

138
00:12:58,007 --> 00:12:59,880
Where?

139
00:13:12,021 --> 00:13:14,512
- Now, see where I'm pointing?
- Yes.

140
00:13:14,690 --> 00:13:19,186
<i>- See them two big trees across there?
- On the other side of the bay? Yes.</i>

141
00:13:19,361 --> 00:13:20,772
<i>- And the white house?
- Yes.</i>

142
00:13:20,946 --> 00:13:24,944
<i>- That's where the Brenners live.
- The Brenners? Mr and Mrs Brenner?</i>

143
00:13:25,117 --> 00:13:27,489
<i>No, just Lydia and the two kids.</i>

144
00:13:27,661 --> 00:13:30,661
- The two kids?
- Yeah, Mitch and the little girl.

145
00:13:31,206 --> 00:13:33,828
Oh, I see. How do I get down there?

146
00:13:34,001 --> 00:13:38,828
You follow the road around the bay,
and that'll take you to their front door.

147
00:13:39,006 --> 00:13:41,757
The front door.
Is there a back road I can take?

148
00:13:41,925 --> 00:13:44,879
<i>- No. That's the only road.
- You see, I want to surprise them.</i>

149
00:13:45,053 --> 00:13:46,631
Oh?

150
00:13:46,805 --> 00:13:49,592
<i>- I don't want them to see me arrive.
- Oh.</i>

151
00:13:49,766 --> 00:13:52,054
It's a surprise, you see.

152
00:13:52,226 --> 00:13:54,598
Well, you could get yourself a boat

153
00:13:54,770 --> 00:13:57,937
<i>and cut right across the bay
to their dock.</i>

154
00:13:58,107 --> 00:14:00,314
Where would I get a boat?

155
00:14:00,485 --> 00:14:03,106
Down by the Tides Restaurant.

156
00:14:03,279 --> 00:14:05,687
Did you ever handle an outboard boat?

157
00:14:05,865 --> 00:14:08,107
Of course.

158
00:14:08,284 --> 00:14:11,867
- Want me to order one for you?
- Well, thank you.

159
00:14:12,038 --> 00:14:14,114
- What name?
- Daniels.

160
00:14:14,290 --> 00:14:16,366
- OK.
- (Shop Bell Dings)

161
00:14:20,921 --> 00:14:22,997
<i>(Rotary Phone Dialling)</i>

162
00:14:28,804 --> 00:14:33,217
- I wonder if you could tell me...
- Yeah. Hold it a minute, please.

163
00:14:33,392 --> 00:14:37,176
- ...the little girl's name?
- The little Brenner girl?

164
00:14:37,354 --> 00:14:39,430
<i>- Yes.
- Alice, I think.</i>

165
00:14:39,606 --> 00:14:43,390
(Calling)
Harry, what's the Brenner girl's name?

166
00:14:43,568 --> 00:14:45,727
<i>- (Harry) Lois.
- Alice, isn't it?</i>

167
00:14:45,904 --> 00:14:48,739
<i>- (Harry) No, it's Lois.
- It's Alice.</i>

168
00:14:48,907 --> 00:14:52,573
- Are you sure?
- Not positive, if that's what you mean.

169
00:14:52,745 --> 00:14:54,571
I need her exact name.

170
00:14:54,746 --> 00:14:58,661
Oh, uh... Just hold on
one more minute, please.

171
00:14:58,834 --> 00:15:00,707
In that case, I'll tell you what you do.

172
00:15:00,877 --> 00:15:06,251
Go straight through town till you see a
little hotel on your left. Turn right there.

173
00:15:06,424 --> 00:15:07,918
<i>- Now, you got that?
- Yes.</i>

174
00:15:08,092 --> 00:15:11,212
Near the top of the hill, you'll see
the school, and just beyond,

175
00:15:11,387 --> 00:15:13,463
a little house with a red mailbox.

176
00:15:13,639 --> 00:15:16,309
That's where Annie Hayworth,
the schoolteacher, lives.

177
00:15:16,476 --> 00:15:19,762
<i>- Ask her about the little Brenner girl.
- Well, thank you.</i>

178
00:15:19,938 --> 00:15:23,353
<i>Save yourself a lot of trouble.
Name's Alice for sure.</i>

179
00:15:24,067 --> 00:15:26,273
Can I have the boat
in about 20 minutes?

180
00:15:26,444 --> 00:15:29,361
<i>- How much for the phone calls?
- Oh, it's nothing.</i>

181
00:15:29,530 --> 00:15:31,569
Thank you.

182
00:15:50,342 --> 00:15:52,418
<i>(Children Chattering)</i>

183
00:15:52,594 --> 00:15:55,714
(Engine Revving & Tyres Screeching)

184
00:15:58,141 --> 00:16:00,430
<i>(Chattering Continues)</i>

185
00:16:00,602 --> 00:16:02,678
(Engine Stops)

186
00:16:21,539 --> 00:16:23,615
(Doorbell Rings)

187
00:16:24,292 --> 00:16:27,043
<i>- (Woman) Who is it?
- Me.</i>

188
00:16:27,211 --> 00:16:29,287
<i>Who's "me"?</i>

189
00:16:32,800 --> 00:16:34,877
<i>- Miss Hayworth?
- Yes.</i>

190
00:16:35,053 --> 00:16:37,378
<i>I'm Melanie Daniels.
I'm sorry to bother you, but...</i>

191
00:16:37,555 --> 00:16:39,631
- Yes?
- The man at the post office sent me.

192
00:16:39,807 --> 00:16:41,930
He said you could tell me the name
of the Brenner girl.

193
00:16:42,101 --> 00:16:43,132
Cathy?

194
00:16:43,311 --> 00:16:45,102
The one who lives
in the white house across the bay?

195
00:16:45,271 --> 00:16:48,390
- That's the one. Cathy Brenner.
- He seemed sure it was Alice or Lois.

196
00:16:48,566 --> 00:16:51,732
Which is why the mail never gets
delivered to the right place in this town.

197
00:16:51,902 --> 00:16:54,571
- I'm sorry. Smoke?
- Thank you.

198
00:16:55,656 --> 00:16:59,868
Did you want to see
Cathy about something?

199
00:17:00,578 --> 00:17:02,654
Well, not exactly.

200
00:17:04,373 --> 00:17:06,449
Oh.

201
00:17:07,084 --> 00:17:09,575
Are you a friend of Mitch's?

202
00:17:10,087 --> 00:17:11,960
No, not really.

203
00:17:13,590 --> 00:17:16,128
I've been wanting a cigarette
for the last 20 minutes.

204
00:17:16,301 --> 00:17:18,377
I just couldn't convince myself to stop.

205
00:17:18,553 --> 00:17:20,961
This tilling of the soil
can become compulsive.

206
00:17:21,139 --> 00:17:23,843
- It's a very pretty garden.
- Oh, thank you.

207
00:17:24,017 --> 00:17:26,425
Well, it's something to do
in your spare time.

208
00:17:26,603 --> 00:17:29,604
There's a lot of spare time
in Bodega Bay.

209
00:17:29,773 --> 00:17:32,690
Are you planning on staying long?

210
00:17:32,859 --> 00:17:34,935
No, just a few hours.

211
00:17:35,111 --> 00:17:37,567
Then you're leaving after you see Cathy?

212
00:17:37,739 --> 00:17:39,612
Well, something like that.

213
00:17:39,782 --> 00:17:42,190
I'm sorry.
I don't mean to sound so mysterious.

214
00:17:42,368 --> 00:17:46,911
- Actually, it's none of my business.
- Well, I'd better be on my way.

215
00:17:48,207 --> 00:17:51,292
- Thank you very much.
- Not at all.

216
00:17:54,380 --> 00:17:57,132
Did you drive up from San Francisco
by the coast road?

217
00:17:57,300 --> 00:17:59,541
- Yes.
- Nice drive.

218
00:17:59,927 --> 00:18:04,221
<i>- It's very beautiful.
- Is that where you met Mitch?</i>

219
00:18:04,807 --> 00:18:06,680
Yes.

220
00:18:08,018 --> 00:18:10,474
I guess that's where
everyone meets Mitch.

221
00:18:10,646 --> 00:18:14,180
Now you sound a bit mysterious,
Miss Hayworth.

222
00:18:14,357 --> 00:18:17,229
Do I? I don't mean to.

223
00:18:17,403 --> 00:18:19,976
Actually, I'm an open book, I'm afraid.

224
00:18:20,156 --> 00:18:23,489
<i>- Or, rather, a closed one.
- (Chirping)</i>

225
00:18:23,659 --> 00:18:26,862
- Oh, pretty. What are they?
- Lovebirds.

226
00:18:28,580 --> 00:18:31,664
I see. Good luck, Miss Daniels.

227
00:18:31,833 --> 00:18:33,909
Thank you.

228
00:18:34,544 --> 00:18:37,545
- Can I get out this way?
- Go right around.

229
00:18:37,714 --> 00:18:41,663
- It'll take you back to the main road.
- Thank you.

230
00:19:08,118 --> 00:19:10,195
(Engine Starts)

231
00:19:31,641 --> 00:19:33,717
(Seagulls Cawing)

232
00:20:01,755 --> 00:20:06,464
- Do you have a boat for Miss Daniels?
- Yes, ma'am. It's the one right below.

233
00:20:09,012 --> 00:20:11,088
(Chirping)

234
00:20:27,155 --> 00:20:29,231
(Motor Starts)

235
00:21:07,360 --> 00:21:09,436
(Motor Stops)

236
00:24:06,827 --> 00:24:09,318
(Motor Cranking)

237
00:24:11,582 --> 00:24:14,499
(Motor Cranking Repetitively)

238
00:24:19,215 --> 00:24:21,291
(Motor Starts)

239
00:25:35,790 --> 00:25:39,739
- Are you alright?
- I think so. What made it do that?

240
00:25:39,919 --> 00:25:42,326
That's the damnedest thing I ever saw.

241
00:25:42,505 --> 00:25:46,454
It seemed to swoop at you deliberately.
Oh, you're bleeding, too.

242
00:25:46,633 --> 00:25:49,670
Let's take care of that. OK? That's a girl.

243
00:25:57,018 --> 00:25:59,094
Come on.

244
00:26:01,649 --> 00:26:03,606
<i>What happened, Mitch?</i>

245
00:26:03,776 --> 00:26:05,982
- Gull hit her.
- A gull?

246
00:26:09,239 --> 00:26:12,904
Oh. Let's try up at the restaurant,
alright?

247
00:26:14,994 --> 00:26:17,236
- Might need a tetanus shot.
- I had a booster

248
00:26:17,413 --> 00:26:19,240
before I went abroad last May.

249
00:26:33,930 --> 00:26:36,385
(People Chattering)

250
00:26:46,817 --> 00:26:49,937
- What happened?
- Hello, Deke. Young lady cut herself.

251
00:26:50,112 --> 00:26:54,157
- Shall I call a doctor?
- I don't think it's that serious.

252
00:26:54,325 --> 00:26:57,610
Helen, get some cotton and antiseptic.

253
00:26:57,912 --> 00:27:02,538
- Um, you cut yourself outside, miss?
- Don't worry, Deke. She did it in a boat.

254
00:27:02,708 --> 00:27:05,033
I had a man trip and fall
in the parking lot once.

255
00:27:05,210 --> 00:27:06,752
Sued me before I could bat an eyelash.

256
00:27:06,920 --> 00:27:09,458
I don't think Miss Daniels
is going to sue anybody.

257
00:27:09,631 --> 00:27:11,255
Well, you're the lawyer.

258
00:27:11,424 --> 00:27:13,298
Thank you.

259
00:27:14,010 --> 00:27:16,335
- What's that?
- Just some peroxide.

260
00:27:16,512 --> 00:27:18,589
I'll clean out the cut.

261
00:27:21,018 --> 00:27:24,221
<i>- So you're a lawyer.
- That's right.</i>

262
00:27:24,396 --> 00:27:27,562
Of course, I usually defend people,
but if I were prosecuting...

263
00:27:27,732 --> 00:27:32,061
- Do you practise here?
- San Francisco. Why are you up here?

264
00:27:32,237 --> 00:27:34,478
<i>- What kind of law?
- Criminal.</i>

265
00:27:34,656 --> 00:27:37,063
Is that why you want
to see everyone behind bars?

266
00:27:37,241 --> 00:27:38,652
Oh, not everyone.

267
00:27:38,826 --> 00:27:42,111
<i>- Only violators and practical jokers.
- That's right.</i>

268
00:27:42,288 --> 00:27:46,037
<i>- Ow!
- Oh, sorry. What are you doing up here?</i>

269
00:27:47,252 --> 00:27:50,039
Didn't you see the lovebirds?

270
00:27:50,213 --> 00:27:53,831
Oh, you mean, you came all this way
to bring me those birds?

271
00:27:54,008 --> 00:27:56,962
To bring your sister those birds.
You said it was her birthday.

272
00:27:57,136 --> 00:28:01,085
- Besides, I was coming up anyway.
- What for?

273
00:28:02,099 --> 00:28:06,559
- To see a friend of mine. Careful.
- Oh, sorry.

274
00:28:06,728 --> 00:28:08,270
Uh... who's your friend?

275
00:28:09,731 --> 00:28:12,484
Annie Hayworth, the schoolteacher.

276
00:28:12,652 --> 00:28:14,727
Annie Hayworth.

277
00:28:15,237 --> 00:28:17,111
Well, small world.

278
00:28:18,282 --> 00:28:20,358
Yes.

279
00:28:21,118 --> 00:28:23,194
How do you know Annie?

280
00:28:23,370 --> 00:28:27,070
We went to school together. College.

281
00:28:27,999 --> 00:28:30,075
Did you? Imagine that.

282
00:28:30,668 --> 00:28:34,369
- How long are you staying up here?
- The weekend.

283
00:28:36,216 --> 00:28:41,341
I think the bleeding's almost stopped.
Why don't you hold that on?

284
00:28:48,770 --> 00:28:51,889
- So you came up to see Annie, huh?
- Yes.

285
00:28:52,065 --> 00:28:55,979
- I think you came up to see me.
- Why would I want to see you?

286
00:28:56,152 --> 00:28:58,440
I don't know, but you must
have gone to a lot of trouble

287
00:28:58,612 --> 00:29:00,688
to find out who I was
and where I lived.

288
00:29:00,864 --> 00:29:03,985
It was no trouble at all.
I simply called my father's newspaper.

289
00:29:04,160 --> 00:29:07,695
Besides, I was coming up anyway.
I've already told you that.

290
00:29:07,872 --> 00:29:11,288
- You really like me, huh?
- I loathe you.

291
00:29:11,459 --> 00:29:14,543
You have no manners.
You're arrogant and conceited.

292
00:29:14,712 --> 00:29:18,045
I wrote you a letter about it, in fact,
but I tore it up.

293
00:29:18,215 --> 00:29:21,631
- What did it say?
- None of your business.

294
00:29:21,802 --> 00:29:23,925
I can't say I like your seagulls much,
either.

295
00:29:24,096 --> 00:29:28,474
<i>- I come all the way up here to...
- You were coming anyway, remember?</i>

296
00:29:30,227 --> 00:29:31,556
<i>(Door Opens)</i>

297
00:29:31,812 --> 00:29:36,225
Mitch? I thought I saw your car.
What are you doing in town?

298
00:29:36,400 --> 00:29:38,855
- I had to acknowledge a delivery.
- A what?

299
00:29:39,027 --> 00:29:42,063
Mother, I'd like you
to meet Melanie Daniels.

300
00:29:42,239 --> 00:29:44,694
How do you do?

301
00:29:44,866 --> 00:29:47,950
How do you do, Miss Daniels?
Acknowledge a what?

302
00:29:48,119 --> 00:29:50,408
<i>A delivery. Miss Daniels brought us</i>

303
00:29:50,580 --> 00:29:52,738
<i>- some birds from San Francisco.
- Oh.</i>

304
00:29:52,915 --> 00:29:55,953
<i>- For Cathy's birthday. Where is she?
- Across at Brinkmeyer's.</i>

305
00:29:56,128 --> 00:29:58,665
<i>Miss Daniels is staying here
for the weekend</i>

306
00:29:58,839 --> 00:30:01,792
So I've already invited her
for dinner tonight.

307
00:30:04,552 --> 00:30:07,719
You did go to the trouble
of bringing those birds.

308
00:30:07,889 --> 00:30:10,889
<i>- I couldn't possibly.
- You did say birds?</i>

309
00:30:11,058 --> 00:30:13,514
<i>(Mitch) Yes, lovebirds.</i>

310
00:30:13,686 --> 00:30:15,762
Oh, I see.

311
00:30:18,357 --> 00:30:21,857
<i>So we couldn't let you get away
without thanking you in some small way.</i>

312
00:30:22,028 --> 00:30:24,104
And you haven't met Cathy,
and you are staying the weekend.

313
00:30:24,280 --> 00:30:26,949
<i>- Well, yes, but...
- You are, aren't you?</i>

314
00:30:27,116 --> 00:30:28,943
<i>- Certainly, but...
- Then it's all settled.</i>

315
00:30:29,118 --> 00:30:32,119
- What time is dinner, Mother?
- 7.00, the same as usual.

316
00:30:32,288 --> 00:30:35,906
- I'll pick you up. Where are you staying?
- With Annie, of course.

317
00:30:36,083 --> 00:30:39,249
Oh, of course. How stupid of me.
A quarter to seven?

318
00:30:39,836 --> 00:30:42,078
Annie may have made other plans.
I'll have to see.

319
00:30:43,215 --> 00:30:44,792
<i>Besides, I can find my own way.</i>

320
00:30:44,967 --> 00:30:47,339
You're sure now?
You won't hire a boat or anything?

321
00:30:47,511 --> 00:30:50,547
<i>- I'm sure.
- Seven o'clock, then.</i>

322
00:30:50,723 --> 00:30:53,640
<i>- Maybe.
- We'll be waiting for you.</i>

323
00:30:54,017 --> 00:30:57,054
<i>- How's your head?
- Much better, thank you.</i>

324
00:30:57,229 --> 00:30:59,980
A gull hit me, Mrs Brenner, that's all.

325
00:31:06,112 --> 00:31:08,188
(Doorbell Ringing)

326
00:31:13,620 --> 00:31:17,071
- Oh, hi. Did you find her alright?
- Yes, I did.

327
00:31:17,248 --> 00:31:19,455
I was wondering...

328
00:31:19,626 --> 00:31:22,164
Uh, that sign there.

329
00:31:23,254 --> 00:31:25,959
Do you suppose I could have the room
for just a single night?

330
00:31:26,132 --> 00:31:27,959
I was planning on renting it
for a longer time -

331
00:31:28,134 --> 00:31:32,594
I would appreciate it. I've tried
everywhere in town. They're all full.

332
00:31:32,763 --> 00:31:35,633
Well, alright. Got your bags in the car?

333
00:31:37,393 --> 00:31:39,884
Well, it's utilitarian, I'll say that.

334
00:31:40,063 --> 00:31:43,063
I just picked up some things
for the night at the general store.

335
00:31:43,232 --> 00:31:48,108
- I hadn't planned on staying very long.
- Yes, I know.

336
00:31:48,279 --> 00:31:50,816
Did something unexpected come up?

337
00:31:51,699 --> 00:31:54,865
Yes. May I use your phone?
I'd like to call home.

338
00:31:55,952 --> 00:31:59,487
I just put some coffee on the stove.

339
00:31:59,664 --> 00:32:04,292
<i>- (Seagulls Cawing)
- Don't they ever stop migrating?</i>

340
00:32:46,419 --> 00:32:48,826
(Doorbell Ringing)

341
00:32:58,848 --> 00:33:00,924
Hi!

342
00:33:01,976 --> 00:33:04,052
(Cathy) Hi!

343
00:33:04,520 --> 00:33:06,845
<i>- Miss Daniels?
- Yes.</i>

344
00:33:07,856 --> 00:33:09,896
Oh, they're beautiful!

345
00:33:10,067 --> 00:33:13,815
They're just what I wanted.
Is there a man and a woman?

346
00:33:13,987 --> 00:33:17,438
<i>- (Cathy) I cant tell which is which.
- (Melanie) Well, I suppose so.</i>

347
00:33:17,615 --> 00:33:19,823
<i>- (Mitch) Hello. Annie had no plans, huh?
- (Melanie) No.</i>

348
00:33:19,994 --> 00:33:21,654
We're very glad you could come.
Are you hungry?

349
00:33:22,288 --> 00:33:24,327
- Reasonably.
- Dinner's just about ready.

350
00:33:24,498 --> 00:33:26,656
We've been looking at the chickens.
Something seems to be wrong with them.

351
00:33:26,833 --> 00:33:30,167
There's nothing wrong with the chickens.
I'm going to call Fred Brinkmeyer now.

352
00:33:30,337 --> 00:33:33,207
What good's that going to do?
The chickens won't eat.

353
00:33:33,381 --> 00:33:35,457
He sold the feed to me, didn't he?

354
00:33:35,633 --> 00:33:39,583
- Caveat emptor. Let the buyer beware.
- Whose side are you on?

355
00:33:39,762 --> 00:33:43,594
- Merely quoting the law, dear.
- Never mind the law.

356
00:33:50,315 --> 00:33:54,229
This won't take long, Miss Dan-
Hello, Fred? Lydia Brenner.

357
00:33:54,402 --> 00:33:57,237
I didn't interrupt your dinner, did I?

358
00:33:57,405 --> 00:34:00,571
That feed you sold me is no good.

359
00:34:00,741 --> 00:34:03,612
The chicken feed.
Well, it's just no good.

360
00:34:03,786 --> 00:34:07,997
The chickens won't eat it.
They're always hungry.

361
00:34:08,165 --> 00:34:11,369
I opened a sack for them when I got
home, and they just wouldn't touch it.

362
00:34:11,544 --> 00:34:13,916
You know chickens as well as I do,
and when they won't eat,

363
00:34:14,088 --> 00:34:17,255
there's something wrong
with what they're being fed.

364
00:34:17,425 --> 00:34:20,176
No, they're not fussy chickens.

365
00:34:21,220 --> 00:34:24,339
Who? What's he got to do with it?

366
00:34:24,515 --> 00:34:26,922
- (Melanie) Is that your father?
- (Mitch) Mm-hmm. Please sit down.

367
00:34:27,100 --> 00:34:33,221
I don't care how many sacks of feed
you sold him. My chickens -

368
00:34:33,398 --> 00:34:35,474
Oh, I see.

369
00:34:36,526 --> 00:34:38,650
Dan Fawcett.

370
00:34:38,821 --> 00:34:43,732
This afternoon? That proves what
I'm saying. The feed you sold us -

371
00:34:45,035 --> 00:34:47,111
Oh.

372
00:34:48,663 --> 00:34:51,830
Well, maybe I'd better
go over and see him.

373
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:55,949
You don't think there's something
going around, do you?

374
00:34:56,129 --> 00:34:58,205
No, never!

375
00:34:58,548 --> 00:35:02,592
No, they don't seem sick at all.
They just won't eat.

376
00:35:03,136 --> 00:35:05,544
Uh-huh.

377
00:35:06,431 --> 00:35:10,215
Well, I'll try to go over and see him.
Maybe he -

378
00:35:11,060 --> 00:35:13,136
Uh-huh. Alright.

379
00:35:14,021 --> 00:35:16,097
Thanks.

380
00:35:18,609 --> 00:35:23,235
He had a call from Dan Fawcett a while
ago. His chickens won't eat either.

381
00:35:23,405 --> 00:35:26,904
It's what you said, Mom.
Mr Brinkmeyer's feed is no good.

382
00:35:27,075 --> 00:35:30,528
No, Cathy. He sold Mr Fawcett
a different brand.

383
00:35:30,705 --> 00:35:34,654
You don't think they're getting sick,
do you, Mitch?

384
00:35:40,005 --> 00:35:42,710
I still don't understand
how you knew I wanted lovebirds.

385
00:35:42,883 --> 00:35:44,792
Your brother told me.

386
00:35:44,968 --> 00:35:46,427
Then you knew Mitch in San Francisco?

387
00:35:46,595 --> 00:35:50,806
<i>- Is that right?
- No, not exactly.</i>

388
00:35:50,974 --> 00:35:55,352
Mitch knows a lot of people in San
Francisco. They're mostly hoods.

389
00:35:56,063 --> 00:35:59,479
- Cathy!
- Well, Mom, he's the first to admit it.

390
00:35:59,650 --> 00:36:03,101
He's spends half his day in the
detention cells at the Hall of Justice.

391
00:36:03,653 --> 00:36:07,105
In a democracy,
everyone is entitled to a fair trial.

392
00:36:07,282 --> 00:36:09,607
<i>- Your brother's practice -
- Aw, Mom, please!</i>

393
00:36:09,784 --> 00:36:13,651
I know all that democracy jazz.
They're still hoods.

394
00:36:15,790 --> 00:36:19,372
He has a client now who shot his wife
in the head six times.

395
00:36:19,543 --> 00:36:22,213
Six times! Can you imagine it?

396
00:36:22,380 --> 00:36:26,212
I mean, even twice would be
overdoing it, don't you think?

397
00:36:26,718 --> 00:36:29,754
- Why did he shoot her?
- He was watching a ball game on TV.

398
00:36:30,513 --> 00:36:32,885
- What?
- His wife changed the channel.

399
00:36:34,934 --> 00:36:39,430
- Are you coming to my party tomorrow?
- I don't think so.

400
00:36:39,605 --> 00:36:42,938
<i>- I have to get back to San Francisco.
- Don't you like us?</i>

401
00:36:43,108 --> 00:36:45,184
Oh, darling, of course I do.

402
00:36:45,360 --> 00:36:48,315
<i>- Don't you like Bodega Bay?
- I don't know yet.</i>

403
00:36:48,489 --> 00:36:51,940
Mitch likes it very much.
He comes up every weekend, you know,

404
00:36:52,118 --> 00:36:55,154
<i>even though he has his
own apartment in the city.</i>

405
00:36:55,329 --> 00:36:58,662
<i>He says San Francisco's
like an anthill at the foot of a bridge.</i>

406
00:36:58,832 --> 00:37:00,908
I suppose it does get hectic at times.

407
00:37:01,084 --> 00:37:05,793
Well, if you do decide to come,
don't say I told you about it.

408
00:37:05,964 --> 00:37:07,588
It's supposed to be a surprise party.

409
00:37:07,757 --> 00:37:10,793
<i>They've got this whole complicated
thing figured out,</i>

410
00:37:10,969 --> 00:37:14,967
where I'm going to Michelle's and her
mother will say she has a headache,

411
00:37:15,140 --> 00:37:17,465
<i>would I mind if she took me home.</i>

412
00:37:17,643 --> 00:37:20,560
Then when I get home here,
all the kids'll jump out!

413
00:37:23,523 --> 00:37:28,185
Oh, won't you come?
Won't you please come?

414
00:37:29,278 --> 00:37:31,354
I don't think so.

415
00:37:34,200 --> 00:37:37,485
<i>- She's a charming girl, isn't she, Mitch?
- Hmm? Yes.</i>

416
00:37:37,662 --> 00:37:39,904
<i>- Certainly pretty.
- Mm-hmm.</i>

417
00:37:40,081 --> 00:37:43,664
- How long have you known her?
- I told you, dear, we met yesterday.

418
00:37:44,460 --> 00:37:46,085
<i>- In a bird shop.
- ln a bird shop.</i>

419
00:37:46,254 --> 00:37:50,002
- She was selling birds?
- No. I just led her into believing

420
00:37:50,174 --> 00:37:53,709
that I believed she was, and then...
It's all very complicated.

421
00:37:53,886 --> 00:37:56,803
But she did buy the lovebirds
and then drove all the way here.

422
00:37:56,972 --> 00:37:58,217
<i>- Mother.
- Yes?</i>

423
00:37:58,390 --> 00:38:01,011
Where did you go to law school?

424
00:38:02,310 --> 00:38:07,650
Forgive me. I suppose I'm just
naturally curious about a girl like that.

425
00:38:08,192 --> 00:38:10,268
- She's very rich, isn't she?
- Yeah, I suppose so.

426
00:38:10,444 --> 00:38:12,900
Her father's part owner
of one of the big newspapers.

427
00:38:13,072 --> 00:38:16,238
You'd think he could manage
to keep her name out of print.

428
00:38:16,408 --> 00:38:20,358
- She's always in the columns, Mitch.
- Yes, I know.

429
00:38:20,537 --> 00:38:25,282
She is the one who jumped into a
fountain in Rome last summer, isn't she?

430
00:38:25,458 --> 00:38:28,661
- Yes.
- I supposed I'm old-fashioned.

431
00:38:28,836 --> 00:38:31,624
I know it was supposed to be
very warm there, but...

432
00:38:31,798 --> 00:38:34,550
Well, actually the newspapers
said she was naked.

433
00:38:34,718 --> 00:38:36,794
Yes, I know, dear.

434
00:38:36,970 --> 00:38:39,805
It's none of my business,
but when you bring a girl like that...

435
00:38:39,973 --> 00:38:41,846
<i>- Darling?
- Yes?</i>

436
00:38:42,016 --> 00:38:45,302
I think I can handle
Melanie Daniels by myself.

437
00:38:45,478 --> 00:38:49,558
Well... as long as you know
what you want, Mitch.

438
00:38:50,900 --> 00:38:53,188
I know exactly what I want.

439
00:38:58,491 --> 00:39:00,318
(Mitch) Be able to find your
way back alright?

440
00:39:00,493 --> 00:39:01,987
(Melanie) Oh, yes.

441
00:39:04,455 --> 00:39:08,038
- (Mitch) Will I be seeing you again?
- San Francisco's a long way from here.

442
00:39:08,209 --> 00:39:10,996
I'm in San Francisco five days a week
with a lot of time on my hands.

443
00:39:11,170 --> 00:39:14,455
I'd like to see you. Maybe we could
go swimming or something.

444
00:39:14,631 --> 00:39:16,707
Mother tells me you like to swim.

445
00:39:16,883 --> 00:39:19,006
How does Mother
know what I like to do?

446
00:39:19,177 --> 00:39:22,629
- We read the same gossip column.
- Oh, that. Rome.

447
00:39:22,807 --> 00:39:24,930
I really like to swim.
We might get along very well.

448
00:39:25,101 --> 00:39:27,852
In case you're interested,
I was pushed into that fountain.

449
00:39:28,020 --> 00:39:30,262
- Without any clothes on?
- With all my clothes on.

450
00:39:30,439 --> 00:39:33,356
The newspaper that ran that story
is a rival of my father's paper.

451
00:39:33,525 --> 00:39:35,981
You were just a poor, innocent
victim of circumstances?

452
00:39:36,153 --> 00:39:38,228
I'm neither poor nor innocent.
The truth of that particular -

453
00:39:38,405 --> 00:39:40,812
Truth is, you're running round
with a wild crowd.

454
00:39:40,990 --> 00:39:44,157
Yes, that's the truth,
but I was pushed into that fountain.

455
00:39:44,327 --> 00:39:47,779
Uh-huh. Do you really know Annie Hayworth?

456
00:39:47,956 --> 00:39:50,198
No. At least I didn't until I came up here.

457
00:39:50,375 --> 00:39:52,083
- So you didn't go to school together?
- No.

458
00:39:52,252 --> 00:39:53,794
- And you didn't come here to see her?
- No!

459
00:39:53,962 --> 00:39:55,836
- You were lying!
- Yes, I was lying.

460
00:39:56,006 --> 00:39:57,879
What about the letter you wrote me?

461
00:39:58,091 --> 00:39:59,834
<i>- Is that a lie?
- No, I wrote the letter.</i>

462
00:40:00,009 --> 00:40:02,465
- What did it say?
- It said, "Dear Mr Brenner."

463
00:40:02,637 --> 00:40:06,136
"I think you need these lovebirds after
all. They may help your personality."

464
00:40:06,307 --> 00:40:08,549
<i>- That's what it said.
- But you tore it up?</i>

465
00:40:08,726 --> 00:40:10,553
<i>- Yes.
- Why?</i>

466
00:40:10,728 --> 00:40:12,686
Because it seemed stupid and foolish.

467
00:40:12,856 --> 00:40:15,097
- Like jumping into a fountain in Rome.
- I told you what happened!

468
00:40:15,275 --> 00:40:19,272
- You don't expect me to believe that?
- I don't give a damn what you believe!

469
00:40:19,445 --> 00:40:21,438
- I'd still like to see you.
- Why?

470
00:40:21,614 --> 00:40:23,156
I think it might be fun.

471
00:40:23,324 --> 00:40:26,111
That might have been good enough
in Rome, but it's not good enough now.

472
00:40:26,285 --> 00:40:27,565
<i>- It is for me.
- Well, not for me.</i>

473
00:40:27,745 --> 00:40:30,282
- What do you want?
- I thought you knew.

474
00:40:30,456 --> 00:40:34,702
I want to go through life... jumping
into fountains naked. Good night.

475
00:40:44,970 --> 00:40:47,675
<i>(Birds Chirping, Squawking)</i>

476
00:40:56,106 --> 00:40:58,431
- Miss Daniels, is that you?
- Yes.

477
00:40:58,608 --> 00:41:00,185
Hi.

478
00:41:01,277 --> 00:41:04,528
Is something wrong?
Is that cut beginning to bother you?

479
00:41:04,698 --> 00:41:07,865
No, it's not the cut that's bothering me.

480
00:41:08,034 --> 00:41:11,984
- Would you like some brandy?
- If you have some, I'd love it.

481
00:41:12,163 --> 00:41:14,535
I'll get it. Why don't you sit down.

482
00:41:14,707 --> 00:41:17,910
Oh, would you like a sweater
or something, a quilt?

483
00:41:18,086 --> 00:41:20,161
No. No, thank you.

484
00:41:23,591 --> 00:41:26,841
<i>- Won't you call me Melanie?
- Alright.</i>

485
00:41:34,018 --> 00:41:35,845
Thank you.

486
00:41:36,020 --> 00:41:41,975
Gets a bit chilly here at night sometimes,
especially if you're over near the bay.

487
00:41:42,651 --> 00:41:45,771
<i>Well, how did your evening go?</i>

488
00:41:45,946 --> 00:41:48,022
<i>Did you meet Lydia?</i>

489
00:41:49,116 --> 00:41:51,867
Or would you rather
I changed the subject?

490
00:41:52,035 --> 00:41:54,111
I think so.

491
00:41:55,413 --> 00:41:59,626
- Well, how do you like our little hamlet?
- I despise it.

492
00:42:00,794 --> 00:42:03,878
I suppose it doesn't offer much
to the casual visitor,

493
00:42:04,047 --> 00:42:07,001
unless you're thrilled by a collection
of shacks on a hillside.

494
00:42:07,175 --> 00:42:09,382
It takes a bit of getting used to.

495
00:42:09,553 --> 00:42:12,257
<i>- (Melanie) Where're you from originally?
- San Francisco.</i>

496
00:42:12,430 --> 00:42:15,466
How did you happen to come up here?

497
00:42:18,061 --> 00:42:21,596
A friend invited me up for a weekend
a long time ago.

498
00:42:23,191 --> 00:42:26,358
Look, I see no reason for being coy
about this. It was Mitch Brenner.

499
00:42:26,528 --> 00:42:29,232
<i>- I guess you knew that anyway.
- I suspected as much.</i>

500
00:42:30,824 --> 00:42:32,448
Well, you needn't worry.

501
00:42:32,617 --> 00:42:34,693
Its been over and done with
a long time ago.

502
00:42:35,411 --> 00:42:38,328
Annie, there's nothing
between Mr Brenner and me.

503
00:42:38,497 --> 00:42:42,709
<i>Isn't there? Well, maybe there isn't.</i>

504
00:42:42,877 --> 00:42:46,043
Maybe there's never been anything
between Mitch and any girl.

505
00:42:46,213 --> 00:42:51,291
- What do you mean?
- I think I'll have some of that.

506
00:42:51,469 --> 00:42:53,960
I was seeing a lot of him
in San Francisco.

507
00:42:54,138 --> 00:42:56,890
One weekend, he invited me up
to meet Lydia.

508
00:42:57,057 --> 00:42:59,383
- When was this?
- Four years ago,

509
00:42:59,560 --> 00:43:01,636
shortly after his father died.

510
00:43:02,438 --> 00:43:05,972
<i>- Of course, things may be different now.
- Different?</i>

511
00:43:07,442 --> 00:43:09,518
With Lydia.

512
00:43:09,694 --> 00:43:12,861
<i>- Did she seem a trifle distant?
- A trifle.</i>

513
00:43:13,616 --> 00:43:16,984
Well, then perhaps things
aren't quite so different.

514
00:43:17,161 --> 00:43:19,830
<i>You know, her attitude
nearly drove me crazy.</i>

515
00:43:19,997 --> 00:43:22,488
When I got back to San Francisco,
I spent days

516
00:43:22,666 --> 00:43:25,121
trying to figure out
what I'd done to displease her.

517
00:43:25,293 --> 00:43:28,413
- Well, what had you done?
- Nothing.

518
00:43:28,588 --> 00:43:33,214
I simply existed. So what's the answer?
A jealous woman, right?

519
00:43:33,384 --> 00:43:35,211
<i>A clinging, possessive mother?</i>

520
00:43:35,386 --> 00:43:40,096
Wrong. With all due respect to Oedipus,
I don't think that was the case.

521
00:43:40,267 --> 00:43:42,592
Then what was it?

522
00:43:42,769 --> 00:43:46,185
Lydia liked me. That's the strange part.

523
00:43:46,356 --> 00:43:48,514
Now that I'm no longer a threat,
we're very good friends.

524
00:43:48,691 --> 00:43:53,020
- Then why did she object to you?
- Because she was afraid.

525
00:43:53,196 --> 00:43:57,738
- Afraid you'd take Mitch?
- Afraid I'd give Mitch.

526
00:43:57,908 --> 00:43:59,284
I don't understand.

527
00:43:59,451 --> 00:44:03,496
Afraid of any woman who would give
Mitch what Lydia can give him: love.

528
00:44:03,664 --> 00:44:06,868
That adds up to a jealous,
possessive woman.

529
00:44:07,043 --> 00:44:09,119
No, I don't think so.

530
00:44:09,462 --> 00:44:14,883
You see, she's not afraid of losing Mitch.
She's only afraid of being abandoned.

531
00:44:15,050 --> 00:44:19,214
Someone ought to tell her
she'd be gaining a daughter.

532
00:44:19,680 --> 00:44:22,431
No. She already has a daughter.

533
00:44:22,599 --> 00:44:27,557
Well, what about Mitch? Didn't he
have anything to say about this?

534
00:44:27,729 --> 00:44:30,136
Well, I can understand his position.

535
00:44:30,315 --> 00:44:32,985
He'd just been through a lot with Lydia
after his father died.

536
00:44:33,152 --> 00:44:35,559
He didn't want to risk
going through it all again.

537
00:44:35,737 --> 00:44:37,813
<i>- I see.
- So, it ended.</i>

538
00:44:37,990 --> 00:44:41,193
Not right then, of course.
We went back to San Francisco,

539
00:44:41,368 --> 00:44:44,037
saw each other now and then,
but we both knew it was over.

540
00:44:44,204 --> 00:44:48,700
- Then why are you in Bodega Bay?
- I wanted to be near Mitch.

541
00:44:48,875 --> 00:44:52,374
<i>Oh, it was over and done with,
and I knew it, but...</i>

542
00:44:52,545 --> 00:44:55,462
I still wanted to be near him.

543
00:44:55,631 --> 00:44:58,549
<i>I still like him a hell of a lot,</i>

544
00:44:58,718 --> 00:45:02,253
and I don't want to lose
that friendship, ever.

545
00:45:03,014 --> 00:45:05,256
<i>(Phone Ringing)</i>

546
00:45:12,356 --> 00:45:14,230
Hello.

547
00:45:14,608 --> 00:45:16,482
Hello.

548
00:45:16,652 --> 00:45:18,940
No, no, no, I wasn't asleep.

549
00:45:19,863 --> 00:45:22,355
Yes, just a little while ago.

550
00:45:23,076 --> 00:45:25,151
Sure. Hold on.

551
00:45:26,204 --> 00:45:28,279
It's Mitch. For you.

552
00:45:37,005 --> 00:45:40,006
Hello? Oh, yes, this is Melanie.

553
00:45:41,676 --> 00:45:43,752
Fine, thank you.

554
00:45:43,928 --> 00:45:47,797
No, no trouble at all.
I simply followed the road.

555
00:45:51,061 --> 00:45:54,430
<i>There's no need to apologise.
I can understand -</i>

556
00:45:55,899 --> 00:45:59,232
That's very kind of you.
No, I'm not angry.

557
00:46:02,864 --> 00:46:06,648
Well, I couldn't.
I have to get back to San Francisco.

558
00:46:08,369 --> 00:46:11,904
No, I wouldn't want to disappoint Cathy, but...

559
00:46:15,669 --> 00:46:17,745
I see.

560
00:46:19,047 --> 00:46:21,372
<i>Alright. Yes, I'll be there.</i>

561
00:46:22,467 --> 00:46:25,551
Good night, Mitch. (Hangs Up Phone)

562
00:46:26,304 --> 00:46:30,467
He wants me to go to Cathy's party
tomorrow afternoon.

563
00:46:30,641 --> 00:46:33,428
<i>- I said I would.
- It should be fun.</i>

564
00:46:33,602 --> 00:46:35,808
<i>I'll be there, too, to help.</i>

565
00:46:35,979 --> 00:46:38,470
Oh, it seems so pointless.

566
00:46:38,649 --> 00:46:42,599
Well, I think I'll go to sleep.
It's been a busy day.

567
00:46:48,325 --> 00:46:50,401
My luggage.

568
00:46:53,705 --> 00:46:58,034
That's pretty.
Where'd you get that? Brinkmeyer's?

569
00:46:58,460 --> 00:47:02,078
- Do you think I should go?
- Well, that's up to you.

570
00:47:03,089 --> 00:47:06,708
No, it's really up to Lydia, isn't it?

571
00:47:06,885 --> 00:47:10,337
Never mind Lydia. Do you want to go?

572
00:47:10,514 --> 00:47:12,257
Yes.

573
00:47:12,432 --> 00:47:15,184
- Then go.
- Thank you, Annie.

574
00:47:16,019 --> 00:47:20,147
<i>- (Clattering Sound)
- Oh. Wonder who that can be.</i>

575
00:47:20,315 --> 00:47:23,351
Is someone there? Who is it?

576
00:47:24,110 --> 00:47:26,186
(Melanie) Look!

577
00:47:27,488 --> 00:47:31,736
<i>(Annie) Poor thing.
Probably lost his way in the dark.</i>

578
00:47:32,577 --> 00:47:34,783
But it isn't dark, Annie.

579
00:47:35,622 --> 00:47:37,698
There's a full moon.

580
00:47:46,340 --> 00:47:48,831
(Children Chattering, Laughing)

581
00:47:49,009 --> 00:47:52,212
<i>(Annie)
Cathy, that's very good. Very good.</i>

582
00:47:52,387 --> 00:47:54,463
<i>(Annie) OK. Here we go.</i>

583
00:48:13,575 --> 00:48:17,703
<i>(Annie) Attagirl. Come on.
Don't let him get you.</i>

584
00:48:32,344 --> 00:48:35,013
I really shouldn't have any more.
I'm driving.

585
00:48:35,180 --> 00:48:38,595
Actually, I'm trying to get you to stay
for dinner. A lot of roast beef left over.

586
00:48:38,766 --> 00:48:42,100
No, I couldn't possibly. I have to get back.

587
00:48:42,270 --> 00:48:44,345
Alright.

588
00:48:44,522 --> 00:48:46,598
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

589
00:48:47,775 --> 00:48:51,690
Why do you have to rush off?
What's so important in San Francisco?

590
00:48:51,863 --> 00:48:55,362
Well, I have to get to work
tomorrow, for one thing.

591
00:48:55,533 --> 00:48:58,238
- You have a job?
- I have several jobs.

592
00:48:58,411 --> 00:49:01,945
- What do you do?
- I do different things on different days.

593
00:49:02,123 --> 00:49:04,530
- Like what?
- On Mondays and Wednesdays,

594
00:49:04,708 --> 00:49:08,457
- I work for the Travellers' Aid.
- Helping travellers?

595
00:49:08,629 --> 00:49:12,543
No, misdirecting them.
I thought you could read my character.

596
00:49:12,716 --> 00:49:16,002
<i>On Tuesdays, I take a course
in General Semantics at Berkeley,</i>

597
00:49:16,178 --> 00:49:18,254
finding new four-letter words.

598
00:49:18,431 --> 00:49:20,803
- That's not a job, of course.
- You mean, you don't have to...

599
00:49:20,975 --> 00:49:24,011
And on Thursdays,
I have my meeting and lunch.

600
00:49:24,186 --> 00:49:27,306
- The underworld, I suppose.
- I shall disappoint you.

601
00:49:27,481 --> 00:49:30,565
We're sending a little Korean boy
through school.

602
00:49:30,734 --> 00:49:33,485
We actually raise money for it.

603
00:49:37,865 --> 00:49:39,942
You see, Rome...

604
00:49:40,244 --> 00:49:43,494
That entire summer, I did nothing but...

605
00:49:44,414 --> 00:49:47,201
Well, it was very easy to get lost there.

606
00:49:47,375 --> 00:49:50,744
<i>So when I came back,
I thought it was time I began...</i>

607
00:49:50,920 --> 00:49:53,957
I don't know, finding something again.

608
00:49:56,509 --> 00:49:59,629
So, on Mondays and Thursdays,
I keep myself busy.

609
00:50:01,055 --> 00:50:04,839
- What about Fridays?
- Fridays? They're free.

610
00:50:06,394 --> 00:50:09,728
I sometimes go to bird shops on Fridays.

611
00:50:11,149 --> 00:50:13,307
I'm very glad you do.

612
00:50:13,776 --> 00:50:16,979
- A nice, innocent, little day.
- Oh, yes.

613
00:50:20,241 --> 00:50:23,609
I have an Aunt Tessa.
Have you got an Aunt Tessa?

614
00:50:24,161 --> 00:50:26,912
Mine is very prim and straight-laced.

615
00:50:27,080 --> 00:50:30,579
I'm giving her a mynah bird
when she comes back from Europe.

616
00:50:30,750 --> 00:50:34,334
<i>Mynah birds talk, you know.
Can you see my Aunt Tessa's face</i>

617
00:50:34,505 --> 00:50:38,917
when this one tells us one or two
of the words I've picked up at Berkeley.

618
00:50:39,093 --> 00:50:41,963
You need a mother's care, my child.

619
00:50:44,514 --> 00:50:47,883
- Not my mother's.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

620
00:50:49,477 --> 00:50:52,514
What have you got to be sorry about?

621
00:50:52,981 --> 00:50:55,187
My mother? Don't waste your time.

622
00:50:55,358 --> 00:51:00,400
She ditched us when I was 1 1 and
ran off with some hotel man in the East.

623
00:51:00,572 --> 00:51:03,407
<i>You know what a mother's love is.</i>

624
00:51:04,492 --> 00:51:07,826
- Yes, I do.
- You mean it's better to be ditched?

625
00:51:09,956 --> 00:51:14,416
No. I think it's better to be loved.
Don't you ever see her?

626
00:51:20,216 --> 00:51:23,336
(Almost Crying) I don't know where she is.

627
00:51:25,555 --> 00:51:29,552
Well, maybe I ought to go
join the other children.

628
00:51:33,354 --> 00:51:35,430
(Children Chattering)

629
00:51:35,606 --> 00:51:38,523
<i>(Annie) Alright. Here we go. One...</i>

630
00:51:39,401 --> 00:51:41,275
<i>two...</i>

631
00:51:42,154 --> 00:51:44,027
<i>three.</i>

632
00:51:44,906 --> 00:51:46,982
There you go.

633
00:51:49,078 --> 00:51:51,367
<i>(Children Laughing)</i>

634
00:51:55,876 --> 00:51:57,952
<i>(Child) Look! Look!</i>

635
00:51:59,421 --> 00:52:01,912
Hey! No touching allowed!

636
00:52:02,090 --> 00:52:04,166
<i>- (Squawking)
- Oh!</i>

637
00:52:04,342 --> 00:52:06,418
<i>(Birds Squawking)</i>

638
00:52:07,429 --> 00:52:09,717
<i>(Children Screaming)</i>

639
00:52:14,101 --> 00:52:15,478
(Loud Pop)

640
00:52:16,855 --> 00:52:19,772
(Squawking, Screaming Continues)

641
00:52:30,743 --> 00:52:33,946
Help me get the children into the house.

642
00:53:08,072 --> 00:53:10,148
There you go.

643
00:53:13,243 --> 00:53:15,319
(Sobbing)

644
00:53:15,495 --> 00:53:18,165
<i>- (Children Sobbing)
- (Lydia) Have they gone, Mitch?</i>

645
00:53:18,331 --> 00:53:19,956
- I think so.
- (Lydia) Is anyone hurt?

646
00:53:20,125 --> 00:53:22,794
(Woman) Jenny got a scratch down
her cheek, but it's nothing.

647
00:53:22,961 --> 00:53:25,202
That makes three times.

648
00:53:28,674 --> 00:53:31,082
Mitch, this isn't usual, is it?

649
00:53:31,260 --> 00:53:35,010
The gull when I was in the boat,
the one at Annie's last night -

650
00:53:35,182 --> 00:53:39,345
- Last night? What do you mean?
- A gull smashed into Annie's front door.

651
00:53:39,519 --> 00:53:42,389
- Mitch, what's happening?
- I don't know.

652
00:53:42,564 --> 00:53:46,395
- Do you have to go back to Annie's?
- No. I have my things in the car.

653
00:53:46,567 --> 00:53:51,395
Stay and have something to eat before
you start back. I'd feel a lot better.

654
00:54:01,290 --> 00:54:04,410
<i>- Would you like some mustard?
- (Melanie) No, thank you.</i>

655
00:54:04,585 --> 00:54:06,245
<i>Why didn't Annie stay?</i>

656
00:54:06,420 --> 00:54:08,709
Said something about taking a call
from her sister in the East.

657
00:54:08,881 --> 00:54:10,957
<i>- (Chirping)
- What's the matter with them?</i>

658
00:54:11,133 --> 00:54:14,134
- What's the matter with all the birds?
- Where did you want this coffee?

659
00:54:14,303 --> 00:54:17,387
- Here on the table, honey.
- Hurry up with yours, Mitch.

660
00:54:17,556 --> 00:54:19,963
I'm sure Miss Daniels
wants to be on her way.

661
00:54:20,141 --> 00:54:23,059
<i>(Cathy) I think you ought
to stay the night, Melanie.</i>

662
00:54:23,228 --> 00:54:25,766
We have an extra room
upstairs and everything.

663
00:54:25,940 --> 00:54:28,228
(Mitch) That road can be
a pretty bad one at night.

664
00:54:28,400 --> 00:54:32,065
If I go across to Santa Rosa, I'll come
out on the freeway earlier, won't I?

665
00:54:32,237 --> 00:54:34,313
Yes, and the freeway is much quicker.

666
00:54:34,489 --> 00:54:37,241
But she'll be hitting all the heavy
traffic going back to San Francisco.

667
00:54:37,409 --> 00:54:40,824
<i>- (Chirping Grows Louder)
- (Cathy) Just listen to those lovebirds.</i>

668
00:54:40,995 --> 00:54:43,202
<i>- (Chirping Stops. Twittering)
- (Melanie) Mitch.</i>

669
00:54:43,373 --> 00:54:45,246
(Fluttering Of Wings)

670
00:54:47,376 --> 00:54:49,453
(Birds Screeching)

671
00:54:55,552 --> 00:54:58,387
(Mitch) Cover your faces! Cover your eyes!

672
00:55:01,015 --> 00:55:04,218
(Screeching & Fluttering Continues)

673
00:56:17,298 --> 00:56:19,587
That's a sparrow, alright.

674
00:56:19,759 --> 00:56:23,424
- We know what it is, Al.
- Did you have a light burning?

675
00:56:23,596 --> 00:56:26,715
Yes, but there wouldn't have been
that much light going up the chimney.

676
00:56:26,890 --> 00:56:30,840
<i>(Al) Sometimes birds are attracted
by light. Sure is a peculiar thing.</i>

677
00:56:31,019 --> 00:56:34,354
<i>(Mitch) Alright, but we've got
to do something about it!</i>

678
00:56:34,524 --> 00:56:37,727
<i>(Al) I don't think I get you, Mitch.
Do about what?</i>

679
00:56:37,902 --> 00:56:40,772
<i>(Mitch) Well, the birds invaded the house.</i>

680
00:56:40,946 --> 00:56:43,235
<i>(Al) What's more likely,
they got in the room and just panicked.</i>

681
00:56:43,407 --> 00:56:45,898
<i>(Mitch) I'll admit a bird will panic
in an enclosed room,</i>

682
00:56:46,076 --> 00:56:49,196
<i>but they didn't just get in;
they came in, right down the chimney.</i>

683
00:56:49,371 --> 00:56:51,696
<i>(Al) My wife found a bird
in the back seat of the car once.</i>

684
00:56:51,873 --> 00:56:53,949
(Lydia) Tell him about the party.

685
00:56:54,125 --> 00:56:56,367
<i>(Mitch) We had a party here
this afternoon for Cathy, for her birthday.</i>

686
00:56:56,544 --> 00:56:59,214
<i>- (Al) How old is she?
- Eleven! ln the middle of the party,</i>

687
00:56:59,381 --> 00:57:01,872
<i>some seagulls came down at the children!</i>

688
00:57:02,050 --> 00:57:04,837
<i>Miss Daniels was attacked
by a gull yesterday.</i>

689
00:57:05,012 --> 00:57:07,763
<i>(Al) Yeah. Were the kids
bothering the birds or something?</i>

690
00:57:07,931 --> 00:57:10,766
<i>lf you make any kind of a disturbance
near them, they'll come after you.</i>

691
00:57:10,934 --> 00:57:14,883
Al, the children were playing a game.
Those gulls attacked.

692
00:57:15,063 --> 00:57:18,514
<i>(Al) Now, Lydia, "attack" is a pretty
strong word, don't you think?</i>

693
00:57:18,691 --> 00:57:22,689
<i>I mean, birds just don't go around
attacking people without no reason.</i>

694
00:57:22,862 --> 00:57:26,066
<i>The kids probably scared 'em, that's all.</i>

695
00:57:26,241 --> 00:57:28,447
These birds attacked.

696
00:57:28,910 --> 00:57:32,243
<i>(Al)
You got quite a mess here, I'll admit that.</i>

697
00:57:32,413 --> 00:57:35,533
<i>Maybe you ought to put some screen
on top of your chimney.</i>

698
00:57:35,708 --> 00:57:39,706
<i>- You want help cleaning up?
- (Mitch) No. I can handle it.</i>

699
00:57:39,879 --> 00:57:42,416
<i>lt shouldn't be too much of a job.</i>

700
00:57:42,590 --> 00:57:44,878
I'll take Cathy up to bed.

701
00:57:45,634 --> 00:57:49,632
<i>- I think I should stay, don't you?
- (Mitch) lt would be nice if you could.</i>

702
00:57:49,805 --> 00:57:51,882
<i>(Melanie) My things are in the car.</i>

703
00:57:52,058 --> 00:57:54,383
- Do you want to go with me?
- (Cathy) Alright.

704
00:57:54,560 --> 00:57:59,103
<i>- (Al) Well, anything else I can do?
- No thanks, Al. We'll be alright.</i>

705
00:57:59,273 --> 00:58:03,401
<i>- Good night, Lydia. Sure is peculiar.
- (Door Closing)</i>

706
00:58:07,739 --> 00:58:10,028
(Shovel Grating)

707
00:58:12,869 --> 00:58:16,203
<i>(Lydia) Mitch. Mitch. Mitch!</i>

708
00:58:17,124 --> 00:58:20,078
<i>- Yes, Mother?
- I'm going to drop Cathy off now.</i>

709
00:58:20,252 --> 00:58:23,087
<i>I'll probably drive over to the Fawcett farm.</i>

710
00:58:23,255 --> 00:58:25,331
<i>- OK.
- (Truck Starting)</i>

711
00:58:28,468 --> 00:58:30,793
<i>(Truck Driving Away)</i>

712
00:59:04,253 --> 00:59:06,328
<i>(Man) Mornin'.</i>

713
00:59:07,799 --> 00:59:10,586
Good morning, George. Is Mr Fawcett around?

714
00:59:10,760 --> 00:59:16,180
I think so, ma'am. Ain't seen him this
morning, but he ought to be in there.

715
00:59:16,348 --> 00:59:18,222
Thanks.

716
00:59:39,162 --> 00:59:42,033
<i>- Dan, are you home?
- (Screen Door Slams)</i>

717
01:00:44,100 --> 01:00:46,176
(Gasping For Air)

718
01:00:49,522 --> 01:00:51,599
(Choking)

719
01:00:58,156 --> 01:01:00,232
<i>(Motor Starting)</i>

720
01:01:01,451 --> 01:01:03,527
(Motor Racing)

721
01:01:27,893 --> 01:01:29,969
(Sobbing)

722
01:01:31,563 --> 01:01:33,639
Mother!

723
01:01:33,941 --> 01:01:36,895
What is it, dear? What's the matter?

724
01:01:38,862 --> 01:01:40,938
(Sobbing) Oh!

725
01:01:47,121 --> 01:01:49,612
Al Malone, the deputy, just called.
He wants me over at the Fawcett place.

726
01:01:49,790 --> 01:01:53,574
Some detectives from Santa Rosa
will be there. Will you be alright?

727
01:01:53,752 --> 01:01:56,788
Yes. I was just taking
your mother in some tea.

728
01:01:58,256 --> 01:02:00,332
Oh, be careful, please.

729
01:02:10,936 --> 01:02:13,012
And you be careful.

730
01:02:20,236 --> 01:02:24,186
<i>(Footsteps Departing,
Door Opening & Closing)</i>

731
01:02:45,302 --> 01:02:47,793
<i>- (Knocking)
- (Lydia) Mitch?</i>

732
01:02:49,306 --> 01:02:51,382
No, it's me, Mrs Brenner.

733
01:02:51,558 --> 01:02:55,686
- I thought you might like some tea.
- Oh. Thank you.

734
01:02:57,439 --> 01:03:00,013
- Where's Mitch?
- Al Malone wanted him

735
01:03:00,192 --> 01:03:04,190
- at the Fawcett farm.
- Why? Didn't Al believe my story?

736
01:03:04,363 --> 01:03:06,854
He was calling from the farm.

737
01:03:07,449 --> 01:03:09,821
- Then he saw.
- Oh, he must have.

738
01:03:09,993 --> 01:03:12,235
<i>They sent for the Santa Rosa police.</i>

739
01:03:12,412 --> 01:03:14,570
What good will they do?

740
01:03:17,959 --> 01:03:21,126
Do you think Cathy's alright
at the school?

741
01:03:21,296 --> 01:03:23,371
Yes, I'm sure she's fine.

742
01:03:25,592 --> 01:03:28,297
Do I sound very foolish to you?

743
01:03:28,470 --> 01:03:30,546
Oh, no.

744
01:03:33,475 --> 01:03:35,551
I keep seeing Dan's face.

745
01:03:35,727 --> 01:03:38,562
And they have such big windows
at the school.

746
01:03:38,730 --> 01:03:41,849
All the windows are broken
in Dan's bedroom.

747
01:03:42,024 --> 01:03:44,515
Try not to think about that.

748
01:03:45,486 --> 01:03:48,321
I wish I were a stronger person.

749
01:03:52,827 --> 01:03:56,278
I lost my husband four years ago,
you know.

750
01:03:57,915 --> 01:04:03,206
It's terrible how you depend
on someone else for strength, and then...

751
01:04:03,379 --> 01:04:07,625
suddenly all the strength is gone,
and you're alone.

752
01:04:12,220 --> 01:04:15,387
I'd love to be able to relax sometime.

753
01:04:15,974 --> 01:04:18,466
I'd love to be able to sleep.

754
01:04:21,105 --> 01:04:26,099
- Do you think Cathy's alright?
- Annie's there. She'll be alright.

755
01:04:28,904 --> 01:04:32,272
I'm not like this, you know? Not usually.

756
01:04:32,449 --> 01:04:35,817
I don't fuss and fret about my children.

757
01:04:39,455 --> 01:04:41,531
When Frank died...

758
01:04:43,460 --> 01:04:47,837
You see, he understood the children.
He really understood them.

759
01:04:48,006 --> 01:04:51,422
He had the knack of entering into
their world, of becoming part of them.

760
01:04:52,093 --> 01:04:55,010
<i>- That's a very rare talent.
- Yes.</i>

761
01:04:57,557 --> 01:05:01,506
(Sighs) Oh, I wish, I wish,
I wish I could be like that.

762
01:05:04,647 --> 01:05:06,722
I miss him.

763
01:05:08,693 --> 01:05:11,647
<i>Sometimes, even now,
I wake up in the morning</i>

764
01:05:11,821 --> 01:05:15,486
and I think,
"I must get Frank's breakfast."

765
01:05:16,158 --> 01:05:21,153
And I get up, and there's a very
good reason for getting out of bed,

766
01:05:21,330 --> 01:05:23,868
until, of course, I remember.

767
01:05:29,588 --> 01:05:31,664
I miss talking to him.

768
01:05:33,550 --> 01:05:36,255
Cathy's a child, of course, and Mitch...

769
01:05:38,389 --> 01:05:40,796
<i>Well, Mitch has his own life.</i>

770
01:05:43,602 --> 01:05:47,765
I'm glad he stayed here today.
I feel safer with him here.

771
01:05:49,524 --> 01:05:52,311
<i>- Would you like to rest now?
- No.</i>

772
01:05:52,569 --> 01:05:54,644
<i>No, don't go.</i>

773
01:05:56,489 --> 01:06:01,198
I feel as if I don't understand you at all,
and I want so much to understand.

774
01:06:02,204 --> 01:06:04,492
Why, Mrs Brenner?

775
01:06:06,124 --> 01:06:09,623
Because my son seems
to be very fond of you.

776
01:06:10,378 --> 01:06:13,829
And I don't quite know
how I feel about it.

777
01:06:16,175 --> 01:06:19,259
I don't even know if I like you or not.

778
01:06:20,888 --> 01:06:25,596
<i>- Is that so important, your liking me?
- Well, yes. I think so.</i>

779
01:06:26,936 --> 01:06:29,344
Mitch is important to me.

780
01:06:29,522 --> 01:06:32,060
I want to like whatever girl he chooses.

781
01:06:34,235 --> 01:06:36,311
And perhaps if you don't?

782
01:06:37,363 --> 01:06:41,312
Well, then I don't think
it'll matter much to anyone but me.

783
01:06:41,909 --> 01:06:44,031
I think it would also matter to Mitch.

784
01:06:45,662 --> 01:06:50,407
Mitch has always done
exactly what he wanted to do.

785
01:06:53,754 --> 01:06:59,175
(Crying) But, you see...
I don't want to be left alone.

786
01:06:59,343 --> 01:07:03,091
<i>I don't think I could
bear to be left alone!</i>

787
01:07:03,263 --> 01:07:05,339
<i>(Sobbing) Oh, forgive me.</i>

788
01:07:05,515 --> 01:07:09,726
Oh, forgive me. This business
with the birds has upset me.

789
01:07:09,894 --> 01:07:13,345
I don't know what I'd do
if Mitch weren't here.

790
01:07:13,523 --> 01:07:17,057
Why don't you try to sleep now,
Mrs Brenner?

791
01:07:18,195 --> 01:07:20,270
I wish I were stronger.

792
01:07:23,199 --> 01:07:26,117
(Sighing) Do you think she's alright?

793
01:07:26,286 --> 01:07:29,286
Do you think she's alright at the school?

794
01:07:29,455 --> 01:07:33,832
- Would you like me to go for her?
- Oh, I couldn't ask it.

795
01:07:34,001 --> 01:07:37,452
- Oh, I don't mind, really.
- Would you?

796
01:07:38,422 --> 01:07:41,873
- I'd feel so much better.
- I'll go right now.

797
01:07:43,302 --> 01:07:45,378
(Sighs)

798
01:07:52,102 --> 01:07:54,178
<i>Melanie?</i>

799
01:07:56,607 --> 01:07:58,683
Thanks for the tea.

800
01:08:18,962 --> 01:08:21,038
(Shuts Off Motor)

801
01:08:23,049 --> 01:08:25,125
(Children Singing)

802
01:08:26,052 --> 01:08:29,218
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee, now, now, now</i>

803
01:08:29,388 --> 01:08:32,591
<i># I brought her home
By the light of the moon</i>

804
01:08:32,767 --> 01:08:35,519
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

805
01:08:35,687 --> 01:08:38,557
<i># Knickety-knackety, rustical quality</i>

806
01:08:38,732 --> 01:08:42,100
<i># Willow-tee, wallow-tee
Now, now, now</i>

807
01:08:42,568 --> 01:08:45,902
<i># She combs her hair but once a year</i>

808
01:08:46,072 --> 01:08:49,108
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee, now, now, now</i>

809
01:08:49,283 --> 01:08:51,655
<i># With every stroke she shed a tear</i>

810
01:08:51,827 --> 01:08:54,532
(No Audible Dialogue)

811
01:08:54,705 --> 01:08:57,706
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

812
01:08:57,875 --> 01:09:01,955
<i># Rustical quality, ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Now, now, now</i>

813
01:09:02,129 --> 01:09:04,537
<i># I brought her home
By the light of the moon</i>

814
01:09:04,715 --> 01:09:07,550
<i>(Fainter) # Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

815
01:09:07,718 --> 01:09:10,588
<i># Knickety-knackety, rustical quality</i>

816
01:09:10,763 --> 01:09:14,178
<i># Willow-tee, wallow-tee
Now, now, now</i>

817
01:09:14,516 --> 01:09:18,015
<i># She combed her hair but once a year</i>

818
01:09:18,186 --> 01:09:21,804
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee, now, now, now</i>

819
01:09:21,981 --> 01:09:25,066
<i># With every stroke she shed a tear</i>

820
01:09:25,235 --> 01:09:28,189
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

821
01:09:28,363 --> 01:09:31,150
<i># Knickety-knackety, rustical quality</i>

822
01:09:31,325 --> 01:09:35,156
<i># Willow-tee, wallow-tee
Now, now, now</i>

823
01:09:35,412 --> 01:09:38,946
<i># She swept up her floor
But once a year</i>

824
01:09:39,124 --> 01:09:41,994
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee, now, now, now</i>

825
01:09:42,168 --> 01:09:45,335
<i># She said that brooms
Were much too dear</i>

826
01:09:45,505 --> 01:09:48,458
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

827
01:09:48,632 --> 01:09:51,835
<i># Knickety-knackety, rustical quality</i>

828
01:09:52,011 --> 01:09:54,929
<i># Willow-tee, wallow-tee
Now, now, now</i>

829
01:09:55,098 --> 01:09:58,467
<i># She churns her butter
ln her dad's old boot</i>

830
01:09:58,643 --> 01:10:02,308
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee, now, now, now</i>

831
01:10:02,480 --> 01:10:05,683
<i># And for a dash she'd use her foot</i>

832
01:10:05,858 --> 01:10:09,143
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

833
01:10:09,320 --> 01:10:11,810
<i># Knickety-knackety, rustical quality</i>

834
01:10:11,989 --> 01:10:14,658
<i># Willow-tee, wallow-tee
Now, now, now</i>

835
01:10:15,659 --> 01:10:19,111
<i># The butter it came out
All grizzle-y gray</i>

836
01:10:19,288 --> 01:10:22,491
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee, now, now, now</i>

837
01:10:22,666 --> 01:10:25,074
<i># The cheese it took legs
and ran away</i>

838
01:10:25,252 --> 01:10:28,538
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

839
01:10:28,714 --> 01:10:31,964
<i># Knickety-knackety, rustical quality</i>

840
01:10:32,134 --> 01:10:35,337
<i># Willow-tee, wallow-tee
Now, now, now</i>

841
01:10:35,512 --> 01:10:38,596
<i># She let the critter get away</i>

842
01:10:38,765 --> 01:10:41,386
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

843
01:10:41,559 --> 01:10:44,478
<i># Knickety-knackety, rustical quality</i>

844
01:10:44,646 --> 01:10:47,600
<i># Willow-tee, wallow-tee
Now, now, now</i>

845
01:10:48,108 --> 01:10:51,856
<i># I asked my wife to wash the floor</i>

846
01:10:52,028 --> 01:10:55,314
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee, now, now, now</i>

847
01:10:55,490 --> 01:10:58,111
<i># She gave me my hat
And she showed me the door</i>

848
01:10:58,284 --> 01:11:00,953
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

849
01:11:01,120 --> 01:11:06,161
<i># Knickety-knackety,
Rustical quality, now, now, now</i>

850
01:11:06,333 --> 01:11:09,536
<i># I married my wife in the month of June</i>

851
01:11:09,713 --> 01:11:12,879
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee, now, now, now</i>

852
01:11:13,049 --> 01:11:16,085
<i># I brought her home
by the light of the moon</i>

853
01:11:16,260 --> 01:11:19,095
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

854
01:11:19,263 --> 01:11:22,217
<i># Knickety-knackety, rustical quality</i>

855
01:11:22,391 --> 01:11:25,926
<i># Willow-tee, wallow-tee
Now, now, now</i>

856
01:11:26,103 --> 01:11:29,306
<i># She combed her hair but once a year</i>

857
01:11:29,481 --> 01:11:33,064
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Hey, donnie-dostle-tee</i>

858
01:11:33,235 --> 01:11:36,770
<i># Knickety-knackety, rustical quality</i>

859
01:11:36,948 --> 01:11:40,233
<i># Willow-tee, wallow-tee
Now, now, now</i>

860
01:11:40,409 --> 01:11:43,576
<i># Ristle-tee, rostle-tee
Now, now, now</i>

861
01:11:43,746 --> 01:11:45,821
<i>(Annie) Alright, children.</i>

862
01:11:45,998 --> 01:11:49,497
<i>Now, please put your songbooks away,
then stand up alongside your desks.</i>

863
01:11:49,668 --> 01:11:52,159
<i>We'll go out for recess
as soon as everybody gets ready.</i>

864
01:11:52,337 --> 01:11:55,373
<i>(Annie) We are not going
into the playground</i>

865
01:11:55,548 --> 01:11:59,712
<i>- until everybody has quieted down.
- (Children Chattering)</i>

866
01:12:02,764 --> 01:12:05,338
- Close that door. Quickly.
- What?

867
01:12:05,517 --> 01:12:07,593
Please.

868
01:12:09,104 --> 01:12:10,977
<i>(Door Closing)</i>

869
01:12:11,147 --> 01:12:13,223
- What is it?
- Look.

870
01:12:15,109 --> 01:12:18,027
We've got to get the children
out of here.

871
01:12:21,449 --> 01:12:25,067
<i>- (Chattering Continues)
- Shh, shh, shh! Alright, children.</i>

872
01:12:25,244 --> 01:12:29,456
Now, quiet. Miss Daniels would like
to see how we conduct ourselves

873
01:12:29,624 --> 01:12:33,075
<i>- during a fire drill.
- (Children Protesting)</i>

874
01:12:33,252 --> 01:12:36,704
I would like you to show her
how quiet and obedient you can be.

875
01:12:36,964 --> 01:12:40,214
- Uh, we're going out of school now.
- (Children) Leave school?

876
01:12:40,384 --> 01:12:42,709
<i>We want those of you who live nearby
to go directly home.</i>

877
01:12:42,886 --> 01:12:44,262
<i>(Children) Home?</i>

878
01:12:44,430 --> 01:12:46,967
I want the rest of you to go all the way
down to the hotel. Is that clear?

879
01:12:47,140 --> 01:12:48,967
(Together) Yes, Miss Hayworth.

880
01:12:49,601 --> 01:12:51,677
Melanie?

881
01:12:54,315 --> 01:12:56,806
I want you to go as quietly as possible.

882
01:12:56,984 --> 01:13:01,361
Don't make a sound till I tell you to run.
Then run as quickly as you can.

883
01:13:01,530 --> 01:13:05,362
- Now, does everybody understand?
- (Together) Yes, Miss Hayworth.

884
01:13:05,534 --> 01:13:07,859
Alright, John, you lead the way.

885
01:13:27,514 --> 01:13:29,590
(Loud Fluttering)

886
01:13:32,852 --> 01:13:35,094
(Birds Shrieking)

887
01:13:41,610 --> 01:13:43,852
(Children Screaming)

888
01:13:49,786 --> 01:13:52,276
(Cawing)

889
01:13:52,538 --> 01:13:55,029
(Screaming)

890
01:14:05,634 --> 01:14:07,710
(Squawking)

891
01:14:43,213 --> 01:14:45,704
Cathy! Cathy!

892
01:14:47,634 --> 01:14:49,959
(Crying. Birds Squawking)

893
01:15:13,075 --> 01:15:15,151
(Honking Horn)

894
01:15:17,037 --> 01:15:19,658
(Clattering, Squawking)

895
01:15:21,917 --> 01:15:24,752
(Squawks Fading)

896
01:15:44,105 --> 01:15:45,979
Daddy, there were hundreds of them.

897
01:15:46,149 --> 01:15:50,442
No, I'm not hysterical. I'm trying to tell
you this as calmly as I know how.

898
01:15:52,238 --> 01:15:54,694
Alright, Daddy. Yes, Daddy.

899
01:15:54,866 --> 01:15:57,986
Well, just now. Not 15 minutes ago.

900
01:15:59,746 --> 01:16:02,996
At the school. No, I don't. Just a minute.

901
01:16:03,166 --> 01:16:06,914
- What's the name of the school?
- Just the Bodega Bay School.

902
01:16:07,086 --> 01:16:09,162
The Bodega Bay School.

903
01:16:10,214 --> 01:16:13,749
Well, I don't know
how many children - 30 or 40.

904
01:16:13,926 --> 01:16:18,219
No, the birds didn't attack until
the children were outside the school.

905
01:16:18,388 --> 01:16:21,141
- Help you, Mrs Bundy?
- I need some change, Mr Carter.

906
01:16:21,309 --> 01:16:23,385
Crows, I think.

907
01:16:23,561 --> 01:16:27,510
I don't know. Is there a difference
between crows and blackbirds?

908
01:16:27,690 --> 01:16:31,687
- There is very definitely a difference.
- Thank you.

909
01:16:31,860 --> 01:16:34,945
They're different, Daddy.

910
01:16:35,113 --> 01:16:37,272
Well, I think these were crows.

911
01:16:37,449 --> 01:16:39,738
Well, yes. Hundreds of them.

912
01:16:39,910 --> 01:16:43,741
Yes, they attacked the children.
Attacked them!

913
01:16:43,913 --> 01:16:48,291
Well, I don't know when,
but I simply can't leave now, Daddy.

914
01:16:48,460 --> 01:16:50,832
Alright. Yes. Good bye.

915
01:16:51,004 --> 01:16:55,084
They're both perching birds, of course.
But quite different species.

916
01:16:55,258 --> 01:16:57,500
The crow is Corvus Brachyrhynchos,

917
01:16:57,677 --> 01:17:00,678
and the blackbird
is Euphagus Cyanocephalos.

918
01:17:00,847 --> 01:17:04,761
Thank you. You have
the number at the Fawcett farm?

919
01:17:04,934 --> 01:17:07,472
Right here in this book, miss.

920
01:17:07,645 --> 01:17:10,136
I can't see that it makes
any difference, Mrs Bundy.

921
01:17:10,314 --> 01:17:13,518
Crows or blackbirds, if the school
was attacked, that's pretty serious.

922
01:17:13,693 --> 01:17:16,860
I hardly think that either species
would have sufficient intelligence

923
01:17:17,030 --> 01:17:21,074
to launch a massed attack.
Their brainpans are not big enough to...

924
01:17:21,242 --> 01:17:25,571
I just came from the school. I don't know
anything about their brainpans, but...

925
01:17:25,746 --> 01:17:28,237
Well, I do. I do know.

926
01:17:29,041 --> 01:17:32,374
Ornithology happens to be my avocation.

927
01:17:32,544 --> 01:17:34,952
Birds are not aggressive creatures, miss.

928
01:17:35,130 --> 01:17:38,002
They bring beauty into the world.
It is mankind, rather, who -

929
01:17:38,176 --> 01:17:41,876
<i>(Helen) Sam! Three southern fried
chicken. Baked potato on all of them.</i>

930
01:17:42,054 --> 01:17:44,592
Yes, may I speak to Mitch Brenner, please?

931
01:17:44,765 --> 01:17:47,470
- Yes, I'll wait.
- It is mankind, rather,

932
01:17:47,643 --> 01:17:51,771
who insists upon making it difficult
for life to exist upon this planet.

933
01:17:51,939 --> 01:17:55,142
- Now, if it were not for birds -
- Mrs Bundy, you don't understand.

934
01:17:55,317 --> 01:17:58,732
This young lady said there
was an attack on the school.

935
01:17:58,903 --> 01:18:00,314
Impossible!

936
01:18:00,488 --> 01:18:02,861
Oh, Mitch? I'm glad I caught you.
Something terrible has happened.

937
01:18:03,033 --> 01:18:06,153
- It's the end of the world.
- Two Bloody Marys, Deke.

938
01:18:06,328 --> 01:18:08,486
What actually happened at the school?

939
01:18:08,664 --> 01:18:10,870
Bunch of crows attacked the school kids.

940
01:18:11,041 --> 01:18:14,540
<i>It's the end of the world.
"Thus saith the Lord God</i>

941
01:18:14,711 --> 01:18:19,289
unto the mountains and the hills,
and the rivers and the valleys."

942
01:18:19,465 --> 01:18:23,000
"Behold I, even I
shall bring a sword upon you."

943
01:18:23,177 --> 01:18:27,127
"And I will devastate your high places."
Ezekiel, chapter six.

944
01:18:27,306 --> 01:18:29,513
<i>(Helen) "Woe unto them
that rise up early in the morning,</i>

945
01:18:29,684 --> 01:18:31,760
that they may follow strong drink."

946
01:18:32,312 --> 01:18:35,728
Isaiah, chapter five.
It's the end of the world.

947
01:18:35,899 --> 01:18:39,730
I hardly think a few birds are going
to bring about the end of the world.

948
01:18:39,902 --> 01:18:41,859
These weren't a few birds.

949
01:18:42,029 --> 01:18:45,315
I didn't know there were many crows
in Bodega Bay this time of year.

950
01:18:45,491 --> 01:18:48,990
The crow is a permanent resident
throughout its range.

951
01:18:49,161 --> 01:18:52,031
In fact, during our Christmas count,
we recorded -

952
01:18:52,205 --> 01:18:54,780
<i>(Man) How many gulls
did you count, Mrs Bundy?</i>

953
01:18:54,959 --> 01:18:57,794
<i>Which gulls, Mr Sholes?
There are several varieties.</i>

954
01:18:57,962 --> 01:19:00,001
The ones who've been playing devil
with my fishing boats.

955
01:19:00,172 --> 01:19:03,007
- Have you had trouble with gulls?
- One of my boats did, last week.

956
01:19:03,175 --> 01:19:05,880
This young lady was hit by a gull
only Saturday.

957
01:19:06,053 --> 01:19:09,386
<i>- I'm still waiting for the Bloody Marys.
- Coming right up.</i>

958
01:19:09,556 --> 01:19:12,473
Could you ask them
to lower their voices, please?

959
01:19:12,642 --> 01:19:14,718
They're frightening the children.

960
01:19:14,894 --> 01:19:16,970
A whole flock of gulls
nearly capsized one of my boats.

961
01:19:17,147 --> 01:19:18,938
Practically tore the skipper's arm off.

962
01:19:19,107 --> 01:19:21,515
- You're scaring the kids. Keep it low.
- Alright.

963
01:19:21,693 --> 01:19:24,267
Yeah, but he's scaring me, too.

964
01:19:24,446 --> 01:19:27,447
Are you trying to say that all these...

965
01:19:28,950 --> 01:19:30,824
Nah, that sounds impossible, Sebastian.

966
01:19:30,994 --> 01:19:33,485
Deke, look, I'm just telling you
what happened to one of my boats.

967
01:19:33,663 --> 01:19:38,788
The gulls were after your fish.
Really, let's be logical about this.

968
01:19:38,960 --> 01:19:42,293
What were the crows after at the school?

969
01:19:42,880 --> 01:19:45,205
What do you think they were after,
Miss uh...?

970
01:19:45,382 --> 01:19:48,005
Daniels.
I think they were after the children.

971
01:19:48,178 --> 01:19:52,341
- For what purpose?
- To kill them.

972
01:19:53,141 --> 01:19:56,011
- Why?
- I don't know why.

973
01:19:56,185 --> 01:20:00,099
<i>I thought not. Birds have been
on this planet, Miss Daniels,</i>

974
01:20:00,272 --> 01:20:04,352
<i>- since archaeopteryx, 1 40m years ago.
- (Door Closing)</i>

975
01:20:04,526 --> 01:20:07,563
Doesn't it seem odd
that they'd wait all that time

976
01:20:07,738 --> 01:20:09,814
to start a war against humanity?

977
01:20:09,990 --> 01:20:13,407
- No one called it a war.
- Scotch, light on the water.

978
01:20:13,578 --> 01:20:15,819
You and Mr Sholes seem
to be implying as much.

979
01:20:15,996 --> 01:20:18,072
<i>Who said anything about a war?
All I said, some gulls -</i>

980
01:20:18,249 --> 01:20:21,499
<i>- (Helen) Want some more coffee?
- No ...came down on one of my boats.</i>

981
01:20:21,668 --> 01:20:24,338
They could have been after the fish,
just like you said.

982
01:20:24,504 --> 01:20:27,209
- The Captain should have shot at them.
- Huh?

983
01:20:27,382 --> 01:20:30,466
Gulls are scavengers, anyway. Most birds are.

984
01:20:30,635 --> 01:20:34,419
Get yourselves guns
and wipe them off the face of the Earth!

985
01:20:34,597 --> 01:20:37,433
- That would hardly be possible.
- Why not, Mrs Bundy?

986
01:20:38,227 --> 01:20:43,766
Because there are 8,650 species
of birds in the world today, Mr Carter.

987
01:20:43,940 --> 01:20:49,694
It is estimated that 5,750,000,000
birds live in the United States alone.

988
01:20:49,863 --> 01:20:51,939
The five continents of the world -

989
01:20:52,115 --> 01:20:54,522
<i>Kill them all. Get rid of the messy animals.</i>

990
01:20:54,700 --> 01:20:57,737
...probably contain more than 100 billion birds.

991
01:20:57,912 --> 01:21:01,530
- It's the end of the world.
- The gulls must have been after the fish.

992
01:21:01,707 --> 01:21:04,993
<i>- (Mrs Bundy) Of course!
- Hurry up, children. Finish your lunch.</i>

993
01:21:05,170 --> 01:21:07,246
Are the birds going to eat us, Mommy?

994
01:21:07,422 --> 01:21:10,257
Hell, maybe we're all getting
a little carried away by this.

995
01:21:10,425 --> 01:21:13,509
Admittedly, a few birds did act strange,
but that's no reason to believe that -

996
01:21:13,678 --> 01:21:17,924
I keep telling you, this isn't a few birds.
These are gulls, crows, swifts -

997
01:21:18,098 --> 01:21:21,514
I have never known birds
of different species to flock together.

998
01:21:21,685 --> 01:21:23,761
The very concept is unimaginable.

999
01:21:23,937 --> 01:21:26,973
Why, if that happened,
we wouldn't have a chance!

1000
01:21:27,149 --> 01:21:29,272
<i>How could we possibly hope to fight them?</i>

1001
01:21:29,443 --> 01:21:32,397
We couldn't, you're right.
You're right, Mrs Bundy.

1002
01:21:32,571 --> 01:21:36,320
- What's the matter? Something wrong?
- We're fighting a war.

1003
01:21:36,492 --> 01:21:39,113
- A war? Against who?
- Against birds!

1004
01:21:39,286 --> 01:21:41,444
I'm glad you all think this is so amusing.

1005
01:21:41,622 --> 01:21:43,413
You've frightened the children
half out of their wits.

1006
01:21:43,582 --> 01:21:47,413
If the young lady said she saw the attack
at a school, why don't you believe her?

1007
01:21:47,585 --> 01:21:50,372
<i>- What attack? Who attacked the school?
- (Mother) Birds did. Crows.</i>

1008
01:21:50,547 --> 01:21:52,835
You're all sitting around here debating!

1009
01:21:53,007 --> 01:21:55,795
<i>What do you want them to do next?
Crash through that window?</i>

1010
01:21:55,969 --> 01:21:58,804
- Mommy!
- Ssh. Put on your coat.

1011
01:22:00,682 --> 01:22:04,596
Why don't you all go home,
lock your doors and windows?

1012
01:22:04,769 --> 01:22:06,394
What's the fastest way to San Francisco?

1013
01:22:06,563 --> 01:22:08,685
- The freeway, ma'am.
- How do I find it?

1014
01:22:08,856 --> 01:22:11,691
<i>I'm going out that way, lady.
You can follow me.</i>

1015
01:22:11,859 --> 01:22:15,275
<i>- Well then, let's leave now.
- Haven't finished my drink yet.</i>

1016
01:22:16,322 --> 01:22:18,445
(Panting) I got here as fast as I could.

1017
01:22:18,616 --> 01:22:20,858
- Where's Cathy?
- She's with Annie. She's alright.

1018
01:22:21,036 --> 01:22:23,111
Al, why aren't you over at the school,
where the attack was?

1019
01:22:23,288 --> 01:22:25,364
I just got back from Dan Fawcett's place.

1020
01:22:25,540 --> 01:22:28,457
- He was killed last night by birds.
- What?

1021
01:22:28,626 --> 01:22:32,410
- Hold it, you don't know that for a fact.
- What are the facts?

1022
01:22:32,588 --> 01:22:35,079
The Santa Rosa Police
think it's a felony murder.

1023
01:22:35,257 --> 01:22:37,048
They think a burglar broke in and killed him.

1024
01:22:37,217 --> 01:22:39,459
How do they explain the dead birds
all over the floor?

1025
01:22:39,636 --> 01:22:42,922
Santa Rosa Police figure
they got in after the old man was killed.

1026
01:22:43,098 --> 01:22:46,966
Were the Santa Rosa Police
at your school today?

1027
01:22:47,144 --> 01:22:49,635
- Are you coming?
- Now take it easy, lady.

1028
01:22:49,814 --> 01:22:52,351
There isn't a bird anywhere in sight!

1029
01:22:52,524 --> 01:22:56,059
"Look at the birds of the air.
They do not sow or reap."

1030
01:22:56,236 --> 01:22:59,403
"Yet your Heavenly Father feeds them."

1031
01:22:59,990 --> 01:23:02,659
<i>Something like this happened
in Santa Cruz last year.</i>

1032
01:23:02,826 --> 01:23:05,743
<i>The town was just covered with seagulls.</i>

1033
01:23:05,912 --> 01:23:09,281
- Please finish your drink.
- That's right, sir. I recall it.

1034
01:23:09,457 --> 01:23:11,782
A large flock of seagulls got lost in a fog,

1035
01:23:11,960 --> 01:23:14,630
and headed into the town
where all the lights were.

1036
01:23:14,796 --> 01:23:17,750
They made some mess, too,
smashing into buildings and everything.

1037
01:23:17,924 --> 01:23:20,000
<i>They always make a mess.</i>

1038
01:23:20,176 --> 01:23:22,465
The point is that no one
seemed to be upset about it.

1039
01:23:22,637 --> 01:23:26,800
They were all gone next morning, just
as though nothing at all had happened.

1040
01:23:26,974 --> 01:23:29,679
<i>- Poor things.
- I'm leaving! Are you coming?</i>

1041
01:23:29,852 --> 01:23:31,928
Alright, alright!

1042
01:23:33,814 --> 01:23:36,186
Well, hope you folks figure this thing out!

1043
01:23:36,358 --> 01:23:38,435
It's the end of the world!

1044
01:23:38,945 --> 01:23:41,518
I'd better get back to the cannery.
What do I owe you, Deke?

1045
01:23:41,698 --> 01:23:43,774
- Sebastian, hold it a minute.
- Huh?

1046
01:23:43,950 --> 01:23:46,026
- I don't want to be an alarmist, but -
- No one ever said you were.

1047
01:23:46,202 --> 01:23:48,775
I think we're in real trouble.
I don't know how this started, or why,

1048
01:23:48,954 --> 01:23:51,077
but I know it's here
and we'd be crazy to ignore it.

1049
01:23:51,248 --> 01:23:54,166
- To ignore what? The "bird war"?
- Yes, the "bird war."

1050
01:23:54,334 --> 01:23:56,410
The bird attack, plague -
Call it what you like,

1051
01:23:56,587 --> 01:23:58,959
they're massing out there someplace,
and they'll be back.

1052
01:23:59,131 --> 01:24:01,004
- Ridiculous.
- Come here.

1053
01:24:01,174 --> 01:24:05,089
Unless we do something right now, unless
we get Bodega Bay on the move, they -

1054
01:24:05,262 --> 01:24:07,338
Look, Mitch.

1055
01:24:07,514 --> 01:24:10,718
Even if this is true, even if all the birds -

1056
01:24:10,893 --> 01:24:14,724
- Don't you believe it's true?
- No, Mitch, frankly I don't.

1057
01:24:14,896 --> 01:24:17,470
- There's no reason I...
- It's happening. Isn't that a reason?

1058
01:24:17,649 --> 01:24:19,191
- I like Bodega Bay -
- Then help me!

1059
01:24:21,945 --> 01:24:23,984
<i>You're an important man.
If you help, they all will.</i>

1060
01:24:24,155 --> 01:24:25,566
<i>- Help how? What do you want to do?
- (Seagull Crying)</i>

1061
01:24:25,740 --> 01:24:27,732
<i>Mrs Bundy said something
about Santa Cruz. (Crying Continues)</i>

1062
01:24:27,909 --> 01:24:29,819
<i>About seagulls getting lost in a fog
and flying in towards the lights.</i>

1063
01:24:29,995 --> 01:24:31,489
<i>(Sebastian) We don't have fog
this time of year!</i>

1064
01:24:31,663 --> 01:24:33,371
<i>- (Mitch) Make our own fog!
- How do you figure to do that?</i>

1065
01:24:33,540 --> 01:24:34,915
<i>We can use smoke pots,
the way the Army uses them.</i>

1066
01:24:35,083 --> 01:24:38,368
<i>- (Melanie) Look!
- (Seagull Crying)</i>

1067
01:24:39,921 --> 01:24:43,621
They're attacking again.
Melanie, you stay in here. Come on, Al!

1068
01:24:45,510 --> 01:24:47,585
<i>(Seagulls Crying)</i>

1069
01:24:49,680 --> 01:24:51,554
Look out!

1070
01:24:52,433 --> 01:24:54,425
<i>(Gull Crying)</i>

1071
01:25:21,170 --> 01:25:25,084
(Muffled) Look at the gas.
That man's lighting a cigar!

1072
01:25:25,674 --> 01:25:29,588
(All Shouting) Hey, you! Watch out!
Don't drop that match!

1073
01:25:29,761 --> 01:25:33,711
Get out of there! Mister, run!
(Screaming, Warnings Continue)

1074
01:25:33,890 --> 01:25:35,468
(Explosion)

1075
01:25:35,642 --> 01:25:37,967
(Indistinct Shouting)

1076
01:26:00,166 --> 01:26:02,242
(Screeching)

1077
01:26:15,014 --> 01:26:16,722
(Screaming)

1078
01:26:28,694 --> 01:26:31,315
(Gulls' Screaming Increases)

1079
01:26:48,505 --> 01:26:50,581
(Wings Flapping)

1080
01:26:55,345 --> 01:26:57,218
(Siren Wailing)

1081
01:27:06,314 --> 01:27:09,979
(Screaming & Flapping
Become Thunderous)

1082
01:27:38,596 --> 01:27:41,466
(Gulls Pounding On Glass)

1083
01:27:48,814 --> 01:27:51,269
(Shrieking. Gulls Crying, Fainter)

1084
01:28:35,026 --> 01:28:37,267
Why are they doing this?

1085
01:28:37,862 --> 01:28:39,938
<i>Why are they doing this?</i>

1086
01:28:40,781 --> 01:28:45,858
They said when you got here,
the whole thing started! (Crying)

1087
01:28:47,287 --> 01:28:50,574
Who are you? What are you?

1088
01:28:50,750 --> 01:28:52,789
<i>Where did you come from?</i>

1089
01:28:54,128 --> 01:28:57,294
I think you're the cause of all this.

1090
01:28:57,464 --> 01:28:59,706
I think you're evil! Evil!

1091
01:29:02,427 --> 01:29:04,301
(Gasps) Oh, God!

1092
01:29:04,471 --> 01:29:06,962
<i>(Woman Sobbing.
Door Opens & Closes)</i>

1093
01:29:07,140 --> 01:29:09,429
<i>(Running Footsteps Approaching)</i>

1094
01:29:09,601 --> 01:29:11,807
I think they're going! (Panting)

1095
01:29:11,978 --> 01:29:14,470
We can get Cathy at Annie's now.

1096
01:29:16,692 --> 01:29:20,226
<i>(Seagulls Calling, Faintly)</i>

1097
01:29:45,136 --> 01:29:47,212
<i>(Crow Cawing)</i>

1098
01:29:47,388 --> 01:29:49,630
- The crows again.
- Shh!

1099
01:29:51,100 --> 01:29:53,176
(Single Crow Cawing)

1100
01:29:54,603 --> 01:29:56,679
(Softly) Come on.

1101
01:29:57,731 --> 01:29:59,807
(One Crow Caws)

1102
01:30:09,035 --> 01:30:11,110
(Wings Fluttering)

1103
01:30:12,413 --> 01:30:14,904
(Fluttering & Cawing Continue)

1104
01:30:27,010 --> 01:30:29,631
Oh, no. Stay here. Stay here.

1105
01:30:32,933 --> 01:30:35,009
(Screams, Gasps)

1106
01:30:38,605 --> 01:30:41,310
<i>Cathy! Where's Cathy?</i>

1107
01:30:48,781 --> 01:30:51,272
<i>(Cawing. Cathy Sobbing)</i>

1108
01:31:04,297 --> 01:31:06,170
<i>(Loud Cawing)</i>

1109
01:31:08,718 --> 01:31:11,006
<i>(Sobbing Continues)</i>

1110
01:31:13,847 --> 01:31:15,923
Mitch, don't!

1111
01:31:43,585 --> 01:31:47,748
<i>- Oh, don't leave her there, Mitch.
- (Cathy Sobbing)</i>

1112
01:31:53,762 --> 01:31:55,838
<i>(Body Being Dragged)</i>

1113
01:31:57,807 --> 01:32:00,096
<i>(Cathy Gasping) Oh!</i>

1114
01:32:03,646 --> 01:32:06,730
<i>(Footsteps Mounting Stairs)</i>

1115
01:32:14,282 --> 01:32:17,402
(Cawing. Door Opening & Closing)

1116
01:32:20,038 --> 01:32:22,113
<i>(Wings Fluttering)</i>

1117
01:32:37,971 --> 01:32:40,510
<i>(Strange, Loud Chattering)</i>

1118
01:32:40,683 --> 01:32:42,925
(Crying)

1119
01:32:44,687 --> 01:32:47,474
(Feathers Rustling)

1120
01:32:48,941 --> 01:32:51,099
(Whispering) Come on.

1121
01:32:52,194 --> 01:32:54,352
- (Sobs)
- Shh.

1122
01:33:02,328 --> 01:33:04,404
(Loud Cawing)

1123
01:33:07,417 --> 01:33:10,122
(Louder Cawing, Nearby)

1124
01:33:19,470 --> 01:33:21,546
(Motor Starting)

1125
01:33:21,806 --> 01:33:26,302
(Sobbing) When we got back
from taking Michelle home,

1126
01:33:26,477 --> 01:33:29,976
we heard the explosion and we went -

1127
01:33:30,147 --> 01:33:33,065
we went outside to see what it was.

1128
01:33:33,234 --> 01:33:36,650
All at once, the birds were everywhere!

1129
01:33:37,864 --> 01:33:41,315
(Sobbing)
All at once she pushed me inside

1130
01:33:41,492 --> 01:33:44,030
and they covered her!

1131
01:33:44,203 --> 01:33:47,120
Annie... she pushed me inside!

1132
01:33:52,878 --> 01:33:54,954
<i>(Hammering)</i>

1133
01:34:02,763 --> 01:34:05,170
Give me another one, darling.

1134
01:34:11,354 --> 01:34:14,106
How long have they been gathering there?

1135
01:34:14,274 --> 01:34:16,350
Oh, about 15 minutes.

1136
01:34:20,571 --> 01:34:23,146
Seems like a pattern, doesn't it?

1137
01:34:24,618 --> 01:34:28,615
They strike, then disappear,
and then start massing again.

1138
01:34:28,788 --> 01:34:30,864
<i>(Hammering)</i>

1139
01:34:36,004 --> 01:34:38,459
Doesn't look so very different, does it?

1140
01:34:38,631 --> 01:34:41,916
A little smoke hanging over the town,
otherwise... (Scoffs)

1141
01:34:42,468 --> 01:34:44,544
You want to try your father again?

1142
01:34:44,720 --> 01:34:46,796
No, I tried a little while ago.
The phone's dead.

1143
01:34:46,972 --> 01:34:49,131
- Still got power, haven't we?
- Yes.

1144
01:34:49,309 --> 01:34:52,428
<i>(Lydia) Mitch,
I'm getting something on the radio.</i>

1145
01:34:52,603 --> 01:34:54,679
Come on.

1146
01:34:59,276 --> 01:35:01,352
<i>(Man On Radio, lndistinct)</i>

1147
01:35:01,529 --> 01:35:05,858
(Lydia) I can't get any of the local
stations. I think this is San Francisco.

1148
01:35:06,033 --> 01:35:08,109
<i>(Radio) " ...and the work
of a team of professionals."</i>

1149
01:35:08,285 --> 01:35:10,776
<i>"In Bodega Bay early this morning,
a large flock of crows</i>

1150
01:35:10,954 --> 01:35:14,371
<i>attacked a group of children who were
leaving the school during a fire drill."</i>

1151
01:35:14,542 --> 01:35:18,041
<i>"One little girl was seriously injured and
taken to the hospital in Santa Rosa,</i>

1152
01:35:18,212 --> 01:35:20,370
<i>but the majority
of children reached safety."</i>

1153
01:35:20,547 --> 01:35:22,706
<i>"We understand there was
another attack on the town,</i>

1154
01:35:22,883 --> 01:35:24,959
<i>but this information is rather sketchy."</i>

1155
01:35:25,135 --> 01:35:29,547
<i>"So far, no word has come through to
show there have been further attacks."</i>

1156
01:35:29,723 --> 01:35:32,178
<i>On the national scene today,
in Washington</i>

1157
01:35:32,350 --> 01:35:35,221
<i>- Well, is that all?
- (Radio Continues, Indistinct)</i>

1158
01:35:36,020 --> 01:35:39,769
I'll have to get some more wood.
Mustn't let this fire go out.

1159
01:35:39,941 --> 01:35:43,061
- Did you get the windows in the attic?
- Yes, I got them all.

1160
01:35:43,236 --> 01:35:45,608
- When do you think they'll come?
- I don't know.

1161
01:35:45,780 --> 01:35:47,987
If there are bigger birds, Mitch,
they'll get into the house.

1162
01:35:48,158 --> 01:35:50,399
- It's a chance we'll have to take.
- Maybe we ought to leave.

1163
01:35:50,577 --> 01:35:52,450
No, not now!
Not when they're massing out there.

1164
01:35:52,620 --> 01:35:54,660
- When?
- We'll just see what happens.

1165
01:35:54,831 --> 01:35:56,289
- Where will we go?
- I don't know.

1166
01:35:56,457 --> 01:35:58,414
I think we're safe here
for the time being. Let's get the wood.

1167
01:35:58,584 --> 01:36:00,244
What happens
when you run out of wood?

1168
01:36:00,419 --> 01:36:02,044
I don't know!
We'll break up the furniture.

1169
01:36:02,212 --> 01:36:03,956
You don't know! When will you know?

1170
01:36:04,131 --> 01:36:08,129
When we're all dead!
If only your father were here...

1171
01:36:09,470 --> 01:36:11,842
<i>(Radio Continues. Sobbing)</i>

1172
01:36:12,014 --> 01:36:15,466
I'm sorry. I'm sorry, Mitch.

1173
01:36:18,145 --> 01:36:21,395
Make yourself some coffee, won't you?

1174
01:36:34,745 --> 01:36:37,699
- Where are they heading?
- Somewhere inland.

1175
01:36:38,499 --> 01:36:40,574
- Santa Rosa?
- Maybe.

1176
01:36:40,751 --> 01:36:43,076
Come on. Let's get the wood.

1177
01:36:54,680 --> 01:36:56,756
<i>(Banging)</i>

1178
01:37:21,123 --> 01:37:24,078
<i>Mitch? Can I bring the lovebirds in here?</i>

1179
01:37:24,252 --> 01:37:27,288
<i>- No!
- But, Mom, they're in a cage.</i>

1180
01:37:27,463 --> 01:37:29,539
They're birds, aren't they?

1181
01:37:32,093 --> 01:37:35,627
Let's leave them in the kitchen,
huh, honey?

1182
01:38:22,308 --> 01:38:26,057
Mitch, why are they doing this, the birds?

1183
01:38:26,646 --> 01:38:31,023
- We don't know, honey.
- Why are they trying to kill people?

1184
01:38:31,192 --> 01:38:33,268
I wish I could say.

1185
01:39:41,761 --> 01:39:43,837
(Gasping)

1186
01:39:45,223 --> 01:39:47,298
(Swallowing)

1187
01:39:49,268 --> 01:39:51,723
I'm sick, Melanie.

1188
01:39:54,148 --> 01:39:57,481
- I want to... (Gagging)
- I'll go with you.

1189
01:40:00,821 --> 01:40:03,395
<i>(Door Slams. Cathy Coughing)</i>

1190
01:40:10,581 --> 01:40:13,118
<i>(Coughing Continues)</i>

1191
01:40:14,126 --> 01:40:16,202
<i>(Door Opens)</i>

1192
01:40:30,892 --> 01:40:34,012
<i>(Birds Singing, Wings Fluttering)</i>

1193
01:40:40,818 --> 01:40:43,689
<i>(Crows Cawing)</i>

1194
01:40:44,572 --> 01:40:48,356
<i>(Many Species Calling, Wings Flapping)</i>

1195
01:40:48,534 --> 01:40:52,615
<i>(Flapping Grows Louder. High-pitched Chirping)</i>

1196
01:40:57,502 --> 01:40:59,578
<i>(Drumming On Roof)</i>

1197
01:40:59,754 --> 01:41:02,458
<i>(Log Landing In Fireplace)</i>

1198
01:41:06,677 --> 01:41:10,176
<i>(Birdcalls, Drumming Rising ln lntensity)</i>

1199
01:41:20,107 --> 01:41:23,227
<i>(Roar, Rising ln Pitch And lntensity)</i>

1200
01:41:23,402 --> 01:41:26,272
<i>(Loud Crashing & Glass Smashing)</i>

1201
01:41:27,739 --> 01:41:30,526
<i>(Loud Screeching Continues)</i>

1202
01:41:31,243 --> 01:41:33,864
<i>(Pecking, Wood Splintering)</i>

1203
01:41:35,538 --> 01:41:37,946
<i>(Screeching, Fluttering)</i>

1204
01:41:41,795 --> 01:41:44,915
<i>(Screeching & Fluttering Continue)</i>

1205
01:41:58,061 --> 01:42:01,180
<i>(Continuous Screeching & Fluttering)</i>

1206
01:42:07,445 --> 01:42:09,652
<i>(Shutter Scraping Shut)</i>

1207
01:42:10,532 --> 01:42:13,236
<i>(Screeching, Slightly Fainter)</i>

1208
01:42:14,077 --> 01:42:16,365
<i>(Lamp Crashing To Ground)</i>

1209
01:42:19,498 --> 01:42:21,206
<i>(Glass Smashing)</i>

1210
01:42:26,630 --> 01:42:29,750
<i>(Shutter Scraping Shut.
Screeching Continues)</i>

1211
01:42:55,950 --> 01:42:59,071
<i>(Screeching & Fluttering Continue)</i>

1212
01:43:05,836 --> 01:43:08,373
<i>(Fluttering, Rumbling)</i>

1213
01:43:19,682 --> 01:43:22,255
<i>(Pecking, Wood Splintering)</i>

1214
01:43:24,896 --> 01:43:27,601
<i>(Louder Pecking & Splintering)</i>

1215
01:43:28,775 --> 01:43:32,642
<i>(Pecking, Splintering.
Continuous Screeching)</i>

1216
01:43:37,950 --> 01:43:40,619
<i>(Hatstand Scraping On Floor)</i>

1217
01:43:53,424 --> 01:43:55,712
<i>(Hammering)</i>

1218
01:44:07,854 --> 01:44:09,930
<i>(One Bird Screeches)</i>

1219
01:44:10,106 --> 01:44:12,182
<i>(Loud Fluttering)</i>

1220
01:44:18,865 --> 01:44:20,988
<i>(Pecking & Splintering)</i>

1221
01:44:27,582 --> 01:44:29,705
<i>(Sounds Diminish)</i>

1222
01:44:33,045 --> 01:44:35,121
They're going.

1223
01:44:35,881 --> 01:44:38,253
<i>(Screeches Fading)</i>

1224
01:44:50,980 --> 01:44:53,056
<i>(Silence)</i>

1225
01:45:33,897 --> 01:45:36,518
<i>(Wings Fluttering)</i>

1226
01:45:46,326 --> 01:45:48,401
Mitch?

1227
01:45:49,120 --> 01:45:51,693
<i>(Fluttering Continues)</i>

1228
01:46:22,277 --> 01:46:24,400
<i>(Fluttering)</i>

1229
01:46:44,632 --> 01:46:46,839
<i>(Fluttering)</i>

1230
01:47:20,293 --> 01:47:22,665
<i>(Fluttering)</i>

1231
01:47:42,440 --> 01:47:44,930
<i>(Gasps. Wings Flapping)</i>

1232
01:47:45,109 --> 01:47:47,185
<i>(Screeching)</i>

1233
01:47:48,862 --> 01:47:50,938
<i>(Whimpering)</i>

1234
01:47:51,239 --> 01:47:53,861
<i>(Fluttering Continues)</i>

1235
01:48:34,032 --> 01:48:36,736
<i>(Whimpering)</i>

1236
01:48:48,879 --> 01:48:50,955
Oh, Mitch!

1237
01:49:03,268 --> 01:49:06,305
Get Cathy and Lydia out of here.

1238
01:49:07,689 --> 01:49:10,180
<i>(Mitch) Melanie! Melanie!</i>

1239
01:49:18,616 --> 01:49:21,736
<i>(Birds Fluttering & Calling)</i>

1240
01:49:34,340 --> 01:49:36,582
<i>(Birds Shrieking)</i>

1241
01:49:49,354 --> 01:49:51,431
<i>(Door Shutting)</i>

1242
01:49:56,445 --> 01:49:58,983
Oh, poor thing! Poor thing!

1243
01:49:59,907 --> 01:50:03,027
Listen, get some water,
bandages and antiseptic. Quickly!

1244
01:50:03,202 --> 01:50:05,325
Bandages. It's terrible.

1245
01:50:08,373 --> 01:50:10,449
Cathy, get some brandy.

1246
01:50:21,678 --> 01:50:24,383
No, no, no! No, no, it's alright.

1247
01:50:24,556 --> 01:50:26,383
<i>No, it's alright.</i>

1248
01:50:26,558 --> 01:50:29,475
It's alright. It's alright. No.

1249
01:50:29,769 --> 01:50:32,260
<i>- (Gasping)
- No. Shh! Shh!</i>

1250
01:50:57,880 --> 01:50:59,956
Cathy, get the lamp.

1251
01:51:14,397 --> 01:51:18,560
- We've got to get her to a hospital.
- We can't. There's no place we can go.

1252
01:51:18,734 --> 01:51:20,810
- There's San Francisco.
- We'd never make it.

1253
01:51:20,986 --> 01:51:23,062
We have to try.
We'll go by way of Bay Hill Road.

1254
01:51:23,238 --> 01:51:26,939
Then we don't have to go through town.
We can't stay here. She needs help!

1255
01:51:27,784 --> 01:51:29,907
I'm frightened. Terribly frightened.

1256
01:51:30,578 --> 01:51:33,532
<i>I don't know what's outside there.</i>

1257
01:51:35,167 --> 01:51:38,203
We'd better get started
before another attack comes.

1258
01:51:38,378 --> 01:51:41,332
We'll take Melanie's car.
That'll be faster than the truck.

1259
01:51:41,506 --> 01:51:43,582
- Can you finish the bandaging?
- I'll try.

1260
01:51:43,758 --> 01:51:45,834
Alright.

1261
01:51:52,141 --> 01:51:56,470
<i>(Lydia) Mitch? See if you can get
anything on the car radio.</i>

1262
01:51:57,480 --> 01:52:01,181
<i>(Soft Cooing, Beating Of Wings)</i>

1263
01:52:33,682 --> 01:52:35,758
<i>(Fluttering)</i>

1264
01:52:44,067 --> 01:52:46,143
(Cawing)

1265
01:52:53,452 --> 01:52:55,528
<i>(Rustling Of Wings)</i>

1266
01:53:06,756 --> 01:53:08,795
(Seagull Cries)

1267
01:53:53,594 --> 01:53:55,467
<i>(Switching Stations)</i>

1268
01:53:55,637 --> 01:53:57,926
<i>(Radio) "The bird attacks have
subsided for the time being."</i>

1269
01:53:58,098 --> 01:54:00,803
<i>"Bodega Bay seems to be the centre,
though there are reports</i>

1270
01:54:00,976 --> 01:54:03,893
<i>of minor attacks on Sebastopol
and a few on Santa Rosa."</i>

1271
01:54:04,062 --> 01:54:06,813
<i>"Bodega Bay has been cordoned off
by roadblocks."</i>

1272
01:54:06,981 --> 01:54:09,057
<i>"Most of the townspeople
have managed to get out,</i>

1273
01:54:09,233 --> 01:54:11,772
<i>but there are still some
isolated pockets of people."</i>

1274
01:54:11,945 --> 01:54:15,029
<i>"No decision has been arrived at yet
as to what the next step will be,</i>

1275
01:54:15,198 --> 01:54:18,484
<i>but there's been some discussion
as to whether the military should go in."</i>

1276
01:54:18,660 --> 01:54:22,278
<i>"lt appears that the bird attacks come in
waves, with long intervals between."</i>

1277
01:54:22,455 --> 01:54:25,076
<i>"The reason for this
does not seem clear as yet."</i>

1278
01:54:25,249 --> 01:54:27,325
<i>(Clicks Of Radio)</i>

1279
01:55:02,536 --> 01:55:04,612
(Starts Motor)

1280
01:55:05,789 --> 01:55:08,494
(Motor Turning Over Slowly)

1281
01:55:23,097 --> 01:55:26,015
(Shuts Off Motor, Puts On Handbrake)

1282
01:56:16,816 --> 01:56:21,609
- Did you hear anything on the radio?
- It's alright. Come on.

1283
01:56:44,636 --> 01:56:46,712
<i>(Turning Doorknob)</i>

1284
01:56:55,647 --> 01:56:57,722
<i>(Gull Crying)</i>

1285
01:56:59,692 --> 01:57:01,768
No. No!

1286
01:57:02,320 --> 01:57:04,395
Shh. Shh.

1287
01:57:18,544 --> 01:57:20,620
<i>(Squawk)</i>

1288
01:57:26,593 --> 01:57:28,669
<i>(Squawking)</i>

1289
01:57:32,265 --> 01:57:34,424
- Mitch?
- Shh!

1290
01:57:35,060 --> 01:57:37,136
Stay there.

1291
01:57:44,194 --> 01:57:46,732
Can I bring the lovebirds, Mitch?

1292
01:57:46,905 --> 01:57:51,234
- They haven't harmed anyone.
- Alright. Bring them.

1293
01:58:08,259 --> 01:58:09,919
<i>(Shutting Door)</i>

1294
01:58:33,200 --> 01:58:35,276
(Starts Motor)

1295
01:58:35,911 --> 01:58:37,987
(Loud Squawking)

1296
01:58:43,627 --> 01:58:47,790
<i>(Car Driving Away,
Bird Squawking lntensifies)</i>

1297
01:58:50,216 --> 01:58:53,337
(Wings Flapping & Birds Calling)